Parliament has not ratified the amendment for Tymoshenko's release
The Ukrainian parliament has rejected, in an amendment to the criminal law, the draft to cancel the paragraph on the indictment of opposition leader Yulia Tymoshenko.
MEPs rejected at second reading the draft amendment to reduce sentences for economic crimes, which could have opened the door to freedom for the now imprisoned former Prime Minister.
Tymoshenko was sentenced in October to 7 years in prison for having made a previously unfavorable deal with Russia for the purchase of natural gas.
The verdict is not final and the court is due to rule on the convict's appeal in December.
Tymosenko calls the ruling political revenge of the regime and has provoked a process of suspicions of bias of the court also in the West.
The bill to revoke Article 365 of the criminal law, on the basis of which the former Prime Minister was convicted, was signed by 147 MPs.
It would have taken 226 votes to pass.
