The diet of an obese child: does not eat breakfast and takes meat for dinner
Over one third of children aged 9 to 13 are overweight, 9% of schoolchildren are overweight and 5% are obese.
As recent research shows, obese children come from families with unhealthy lifestyles.
This again shows how important the environment in which the human being evolves and the models that surround him are.
For example, the proportion of meat products on the tables of obese children is 50% higher than that of normal-weight families.
19% of obese had French fries for dinner according to survey conducted with awareness campaign "Obesity is not an accident"
In families with small children, sport is also not a habit, which is now the case for most schoolchildren today - only 15% said that at least once a week parents found time for active movement.
Survey of 900 children
The survey was carried out during the last school year and involved 900 pupils from primary schools in the Czech Republic.
This was the second edition of the 'Obesity is not an accident' campaign, supported by the General Health Insurance and the Unilever company.
Since the beginning, more than 12000 students from the sixth to the third grade have enrolled in this project.
One of the key factors driving a dramatic increase in the number of overweight and even obese children is the lack of proper nutrition and physical exercise.
"Only half of the children surveyed said that eating five times a day, for example, breakfast - lunch - snack - dinner, is one of the basic principles of a healthy diet", says one of the survey results.
No breakfast and no meatballs for dinner .
Experts point out that for healthy development, some basic things are needed, such as a family breakfast at the same time.
In the Czech Republic, only 23% of the families of the students eat at the same time as me.
In most families, breakfast is eaten alone.
And the worst thing that's been found is that one tenth of the population doesn't eat breakfast at all.
Breakfast is the basis of a healthy diet.
The questionnaire showed that obese children's families are more likely to eat unhealthy fries.
Almost every student - not to mention the weight - drinks sugary drinks every day (70%).
More than 40 percent of the children surveyed regularly participate in sports, but only 15 percent of the parents do.
You make your own food
Another part of the survey allowed selected children (204 boys and 172 girls from 13 schools) to prepare their own food from the possibilities offered according to their own tastes and personal opinions.
"The preferences of Czech children aged 12 to 15 are far from ideal when it comes to healthy eating".
Among their favorite foods are many cakes, meat, and sweets.
"The most alarming is a strong preference for sweetened lemonade", says the survey.
For lunch, pasta took first place, just ahead of white meat.
The children did not want any starches and the preference for fish and vegetable meals was very low.
The health sector
The survey also showed that children are prepared to change their habits once they receive ad hoc information.
"A group of survey participants who completed the questionnaire after the 'Obesity is not an accident' awareness session showed a strong desire to switch to a healthy diet", the survey results state.
The most striking was for example the case of sugary lemonade, as children began to give preference to drinking water.
The children most often checked white meat and fish as the main dish and would cut down on sweet dishes and "knedliky" (Czech special bread-and-potatoes).
Stylists must also be good psychologists, say professionals
In an introductory article about how to learn for stylists, I got a little angry that there were so many of them at the beginning.
