The presentations of three professionals in the field, the costumes of the characters and a seminar on what is happening on the ground.
And it will get worse.
The closer we get to the final exams, the more practical exercises and information await us.
And even when there are classes on Saturdays and Sundays it's really "drunk".
This time we have with the headmistress Alenka (in the class there are no boys) dealt with how to dress the woman who does not have standard measurements.
And women like that are the majority.
One has a small neck, the other a boy's body, without any particular curve, another overweight.
The stylist must know how to visually reduce the width of arms, lengthen the neck or add the necessary curves.
We've managed to emphasize the character nicely and also not dress too flashy types of women like Jennifer Lopez with a strong chest and pronounced hips and a thin waist.
If there is a difference between the waist and the hips, for example, so that the skirt or pants do not fit at all, it is worthwhile to have it made to measure.
And you won't regret it because a flawlessly fitting garment is priceless.
You will feel much better in a custom-made skirt than in one that is constantly slipping, winding and not sticking to the belt and so on.
For those with a masculine appearance, they may have the luxury of Tucker-style clothing, with pieces of fabric sewn together, or even embroidered.
There are obviously many examples of different appearances and I am glad that I have all week to sort through all the information received.
But I'm also afraid that in terms of what I have to do at home there's too much.
Each intern was given a celebrity to dress for the day and evening.
We must take into account the current appearance, the type of fashion of the personality as well as his appearance.
I'll have to dress Miranda Kerr, who you may know from the Victoria's Secret campaign.
Deep down, I'm glad, because it's better than dressing Britney Spears, Christina Aguilera who has gained almost a hundred kilos recently (don't take my statement, please, completely seriously) or the young Selena Gomez.
We have to cut and sew from magazines or search the Internet, print and work on the graphic design.
The Moodboard, as we say for the final result, expresses our personal style as well as our relationship with graphic design.
It is also important to consider the graphic part of the styling.
The stylist not only dresses the body but creates, for example, productive pages in magazines (on products given trends for handbags, coats, etc.).
Mario Kamenik, stylist and graphic designer, has brought us all this.
But that... until Sunday.
The stylist has to have a big-picture vision.
Three guests from the special added a different twist to Saturday's session, filled with information on the different types of characters.
Honza Pokorny, stylist, Jakub Polanka, fashion graphic designer and Ben Renc, fashion photographer. This is the first time we've had a meeting with the two.
Jakub reminded us that fashion is an illusion and the stylist should know how to use it.
And a talented stylist knows how to work with a single garment in a different way.
Variability is paramount in this example.
Like this trench coat that should be worn in a classic way with jeans and a t-shirt as a light coat but also it can also dress the naked body, with scarves and take it as a dress.
Or just roll up your sleeves or collar and you instantly have a new look.
"Play with it", he stressed.
But I especially appreciated the following advice: "For the job you need to know the rules perfectly".
"You can then start to counter it", Jakub said.
I finally understand why we try so hard to learn these rules, what to do with them, to what, why, when in fashion magazines we sometimes see something else.
No statements on the fashion shows.
I know again, from fashion photographer Ben, that the stylist must have many more variations of clothing than the ones that are photographed.
This means that for a fashion story that will have ten pages (so a dozen models) I must be ready to "retail" at least fifteen of them.
And also, a garment and its combination with other elements appear completely different from reality.
We have to take that into account when creating a model.
The fact that image and style are sometimes half of success was confirmed to us by Honza Pokorny.
Just look at Madonna, who's not a super singer, but her image and marketing made her a global star.
In the Czech Republic, the approach to the use of stylists' services remains frosty.
And familiar faces sometimes consider them useless (as long as I know something but what I look like is secondary).
And if someone gets a styling done on us, we then have to rely on the fact that he will dictate to us with a high probability a completely different (smaller) size than the one he actually has.
Then we just need to go to Google and see if the tabloids are reporting on the celebrity in question, whether she's lost weight or gained weight, etc.
Honza and Mario made it clear to us on Sunday that it is not enough for a stylist to know fashion and to know how to assemble models.
He has to communicate with the people he's dressing and so it's important to be a good psychologist.
You know, you have to be able to guess people, not flatter yourself, keep your own opinions.
"When a manager asks you to sort out her wardrobe and fill it with new items you can't just throw it all away and say, 'Oh, my God, that's horrible.'"
"You will find some things that you find pretty and you will advise him how to wear them", says Mario.
This one showed us exactly what everything should contain, what is called the "placovka" or stylist's bag.
It's the one you hang around your waist and carry around with you for whatever you need.
In addition to clearly defined items such as scissors, hair removal rollers, and baby pins, there are also nylon threads (which the stylist uses to photograph products such as bags or hats), special clips with which to close a garment in the back if it is too large (the pin or other type of clip is not used because it could damage the garment) or a sewing kit.
So that we would not just be people who listened but who tried something in a practical way, they taught us how to properly fit shoes.
And during the photo shoot in the flat-surface studio, the sole could be damaged, let alone the outside.
And so we stuck and stuck.
We were not allowed to touch the scissors to avoid accidentally injuring ourselves.
So it really does take skill.
Mario made me happy when he congratulated me on my creation.
The account I'm reporting is not for my girlfriend.
This is just a small summary of what we learned during the second weekend of classes
