The need for speed is being fought all over America.
Reviewed
What started out as a smooth ride turns into a routine morning commute to work because of a bunch of stupid mistakes by people who have nothing to do with it.
It fulfils everyone's ambition to some extent but it's useless if no one wants to do anything more.
The new game, subtitled The Run, has generated high expectations ahead of its release.
It promised to take a new direction with the already aged Need for Speed racing series and to bring out a kind of game from the playable parts that would not just count with points.
So we were curious to see what the extra scenes would be like where the main character gets out of the car and does whatever he wants.
As is already done in the NFS series, the result is completely different from what we expected.
These are potentially arcade racing games but the whole thing is going downhill because of some unnecessary bugs that have been around for years.
These are not really mistakes but rather the expression of incomprehensible sloth on the part of the developers.
The adventure starts off well.
You are caught up in the adventure of which the main character Jack has character problems and to solve them starts to participate in illegal races across America.
You're behind the wheel on the West Coast in San Francisco, and your mission is to be the first to New York.
There are some interesting elements to the idea.
The route is divided into ten stages and then into more than 50 courses.
As a result, each race is on a different route and the stages are set in different environments that are quite distinct from each other and interesting.
The player does not feel for a moment that the game offers him something identical.
Some environments are of course quite nice even if the graphic technical level is of the same type as the previous series.
It's not the end of the world.
But driving through the desert, in autumn landscapes or in snow-capped mountains is very pleasing to the eye.
The tests are also sometimes accompanied by an atypical element.
For example, in the desert you find yourself in a sandstorm that significantly reduces your visibility.
Then in the mountains you have to be careful not to get hit by an avalanche.
Besides that, the different races are neatly arranged one after the other.
There are only a few of them, but that's enough.
There are moments when you are trying to outrun the required number of opponents (as in a classic race) and then you are racing against the clock (classic duel with the stopwatch) and then you are waiting for another duel with an opponent.
Every once in a while you also have the police coming in and trying to make things difficult for you.
The new thing is the off-vehicle passages.
It's more of an interactive animation where most of the time Jack is running away from someone and you have to help him by hitting the right button at the right time.
It's not that complicated.
What's surprising is that there are fewer of these moments than you'd expect (there are actually only three).
The result is that this element is not likely to be an obstacle and is, in the context described above, in the elements that make gambling enjoyable.
The driving pattern is in the tradition of the previous games.
Which means that there's nothing extraordinary about it at the moment, but it's not necessarily a negative thing.
As for the realistic simulation, you'll have to look elsewhere.
But although we can find better in the competition the driving model goes very well with the type of design of the races.
So it's all right.
The problems start to show up after a while.
Unlike the driving model, the collision model is not yet developed.
We don't expect this game to be complicated and deformed and collision-prone, but when you don't have any idea of how your car is behaving when you're in a collision with any object, it's not quite good.
In close overtaking, you sometimes touch each other slightly, but otherwise your car goes into a frenzy.
Or it's found in pieces.
Thanks to the reboot system, it's not really a problem, but it really annoys you.
The restart is done so that when you've broken the figure or you've gone out of the set the game takes you back to the moment of the last point on the itinerary.
But you only have five reboots.
When you've used all five reboots you have to start the game over from the beginning.
So it's more a tool, in case something goes wrong, than something you can really count on.
Sometimes restarting doesn't help and you have to find the solution by memorizing the route piece in question.
The great thing about this game is that the same actions end up in the same places.
For example, there are certain corners that you have to go through in a certain way or else you won't.
Otherwise, you will meet "civilian" vehicles in a given place, always in the same configuration as you arrived first, fifth, 5 seconds ahead or one minute behind.
What is irritating are situations where you see the opponent easily pass between two cars coming in the opposite direction and when you arrive, you have to either move to the side and outline them or brake.
It doesn't matter if you go in front of it because it's "calculated" in such a way that for the given situation it always comes right up to your nose.
Opponents have other advantages.
Throughout the game, you arrive at certain places, again without caring about the weather, and you always have the same opponent who is in the same place before you.
It's most annoying at the end of the game when you're driving on a long bridge in reverse.
The enemy must pass in front of you at all costs.
When it passes you it blocks your view of the other vehicles in the opposite direction and you get into a lot of collisions.
We can understand that the goal of this game is to do something exciting and adrenaline-filled, but it's clear that you get bored quickly.
And that's a shame because through a simple behavior pattern the game is interesting and places with so much action that you don't have time to follow everything that's going on.
And it doesn't matter if it's because of the concept of 50 unique routes, that the order of the races is such that there's no chance of boredom or anything else.
The original idea is to change cars during the races.
You have to be careful at the petrol stations on the routes because you can change cars there, but most of the time the one you have is enough.
Cars are divided into three categories.
Sports cars are ideal for cities, American big-displacement cars for straight highways and super sports cars with exotic features on highly technical roads such as mountain lace roads.
And the challenge mode, which is racing in particular places that you know from adventure, goes very well with the main story mode.
You not only receive medals but also experience points that add to your profile that is common to challenges and adventure.
When you reach the highest conductor level, various objects begin to unlock:
It connects online with the Autolog function which among other things compares your scores with those of other players and provides you with other functions in the community.
One of the hardest hits to take is the situation of the last race of the adventure.
You drive your car into the subway tunnel (it looks like) where you drive in the dark on the tracks (it looks like).
Your speedometer tells you between 90 and 100 miles an hour (pre-arranged), and behind you comes a subway train that sends your car straight to the scrap heap.
In the editorial department we had a discussion for a few days about whether someone really thought when creating this game or whether the authors really think we're idiots.
The technical part of the game is not extra, but the visual part is generally pleasant and in some cases really great.
What's troubling is that in more extreme situations, the imagery doesn't hold up and in some cases tragically.
This is especially true for accidents with a large number of participants when a fluid imaging system is no longer useful.
The sound part is good and the track is choice.
In an effort to appeal to the largest number and especially the youngest audience a new soundtrack has been created in the style of "I mix everything", but one can expect that no one will buy the game for the music.
So the overall impression of Need for Speed: The Run is really confusing.
If the game didn't have these stupid mistakes we could say without fear that this is the best production of NFS in recent years.
But this game feels like it's not over.
The fun is great, but be prepared for the mistakes to hit you in the eye with the force of an airfield reflector.
The Students of Velour in concert with the Choirs of Charles University
The Festa Academica festival is offering for the third time festivities that link the International Students' Day with the anniversary of the Velvet Revolution with a musical part.
During the festival 20 choirs from the upper secondary schools and classes perform.
The festival culminated in two organ concerts on 17 November.
"Charles University has a big part in this festival".
"Among the choirs is the Choir of the Faculty of Pedagogy and Humanities, and the festival committee is headed by the rector Vaclav Hampl", says the head of the organising team Jakub Calou.
The highlight of the festival is the concert of the Choir of Secondary Schools and Classes which takes place with free admission on November 17 from 2 pm on the space located in front of the National Technical Library in Dejvice.
The program includes the composition of the well-known Czech jazzman Karel Ruzicka, Celebration Jazz mass.
In the evening, the "Students of Velvet" concert takes place in the National House in Vinohrady, with the choirs of the higher schools and the Charles University.
The Festa Academica aims not only to celebrate the International Students' Day with dignity and to commemorate the 22nd anniversary of the Velvet Revolution, but also to present to the public choir music of the highest level and to develop the creative cooperation of young people.
The main organiser is the Union of Czech Churches in cooperation with the Jan Kepler High School.
The whole action is placed under the aegis of Bohuslav Svoboda, Mayor of Prague and Vaclav Hampl, Rector of Charles University.
The festival takes place from 16 to 20 November in Prague and Pardubice.
The programme also includes high-level concerts, musical meetings, a student happening and other activities.
All information is available on the website of the festival www.festaacademica.cz.
Vice-President, Ambassador to the European Union:
Czechs behave like negativeists and Eurosceptics
"The Lisbon Treaty has radically removed the balance between the institutions"
"I didn't expect such a hard war".
"It will take 5.6 years before the situation calms down and all the players get used to their new role", began Milena Vicenova, the Czech ambassador to the European Union, in her speech at the Faculty of Law.
When she succeeded in describing the different EU bodies and their relations in such a clear and visible way that many lecturers at the Faculty of Law at Charles University could envy her, she showed how seriously she takes her motto 'understandably and openly about Europe'.
Mrs Vicenova paid tribute to the work of Herman Van Rompuye, the new permanent President of the European Council.
"From the beginning, the criticism was that he was dull, that he was a total loser, that he could not fulfill any mission and I must say that he took everyone's breath away because he played his part perfectly".
