In addition to a successful Czech presidency, she then underlined the strength and cooperation of the Visegrad Group.
"Believe me, when the Polish, the Hungarian, the Slovak come to me, this Frenchman says to me: 'Hey, what are you doing there, what is this group from Visegrad doing?' and he is not at all happy".
The Commission has also proposed that the Council should be able to take decisions on the basis of the results of the negotiations.
The concept of a two-speed Europe, or even a multi-speed Europe, prevails rather than a 'new European federation'.
"We have countries in the eurozone and some outside the eurozone".
"We have the Schengen area, we also have the institute for enhanced cooperation".
First of all, it was said that those countries that wanted to cooperate with each other and those that did not wanted to cooperate with each other stayed in their corner".
"There will be many such institutes and there will be a truly two-speed Europe", she expects.
In this respect, it also welcomed the Czech Republic and Herman Van Rompuye's mission to establish the basis for all EU-related issues to be discussed among all EU members, not just euro-zone members.
The history of a brand:
The innovative IBM begins the second century of its existence
If anyone were to look for the closest word to IBM's strategy, the closest would be "long-term".
For a large public IBM is the symbol of the technological revolution, is a firm felt as very current and yet since its creation it has passed a hundred years.
The foundation for this long-term strategy was laid by the firm's first chief, the visionary Thomas J. Watson Sr.
He left behind the slogan that many of the world's problems can be solved if people are willing to think.
The slogan "PENSE'!" became the banner around which the life of a future giant would develop (and also the title of the internal magazine that IBM began publishing in 1935).
This was the basis of the care company culture that Watson had developed.
For us IBM means long-term thinking of continuous movements towards the future.
IBM survived a hundred years because it always stayed true to its core values and yet was not afraid to change everyone around it.
It's enabled us in our first century to transform technology, business and society.
We hope that in the second century we will achieve even more", said the firm's current director, Samuel J. Palmisano.
A well-prepared system
Watson, in the 1930s, started taking care of his employees like Bata in the Czech Republic -- the IBM people were the only among the first American employees to have paid vacation, employer-paid insurance plus a stylish employee uniform and a well-crafted reward system for inventors and salespeople.
In the same way IBM has a well-developed customer relationship system.
The company was a brilliant early-stage talent scout -- one of the first firms to abolish all forms of discrimination and thus have a choice.
The current plan is completely in the spirit of the anti-discrimination strategy since it will be a woman - Virginia Rometty - who should replace Palmisano as head of IBM.
She has worked for IBM for thirty years and is currently Head of Sales, Marketing and Strategy.
IBM in the last few years has been doing what is called jamy, online brainstorming from which many future strategies and innovations have come.
It's no wonder he has a lot of ideas - the firm has nearly 500,000 people working for it.
An Institution with a Good Name
It is the internal and external image of the firm that ensures its secure position in the business world.
"From the beginning, IBM was more an institution than a technology company", said Rosabeth Moss Kanter, a professor of economics at Harvard Business School and author of the IBM book.
"IBM is not a technology firm but a firm that helps solve business problems using its technology", added Geogre Colony of the consulting firm Forrester Research.
As the firm itself says there is a difference between entering the market and creating the market.
