How travel prices have changed since 1989
Until 1989 there were only 5 state travel agencies in Czechoslovakia: Cedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autotourist.
Travel agencies at this time offered trips mainly to the countries of the socialist bloc, as trips to the west were very limited.
Czech tourists travelled for holidays to East Germany, the Soviet Union (Sochi, Crimea and the Black Sea), Bulgaria, Romania (both on the Black Sea) and Hungary (Balaton).
A major exception was the period from 1962 to 1972 when he was allowed to travel to Yugoslavia and then the regime began to have a Western bias and travel to Yugoslavia was very limited for Czech tourists.
The great paradox of the socialist era was that it was not allowed for citizens of the socialist bloc (also for Czechoslovaks) to travel individually even within the socialist countries.
In the case of the Czechoslovak citizen wishing to travel individually to Poland or the Soviet Union, for example, he needed an invitation letter otherwise the individual trip was not allowed.
Travel agencies at that time also offered trips to the West, but you had to either stand in line all night with a sleeping bag or have a "good acquaintance" in the travel agency.
And even after that, it was still not won.
The currency agreement that was the condition for traveling west was denied to the politically incorrect people who couldn't travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not, however, exchangeable and it was not possible to obtain financial means without the currency agreement (Western currency) to travel to the West.
The Czech people spent most of their holidays in the country, so there were many country houses and cottages that the Czechs bought and this practice continues to this day.
Travel in the Czech Republic has undergone a major change since 1989.
Although until 1989 holidays in East Germany and Bulgaria were at their peak, last year the Czechs spent 4 million days abroad on holidays in countries around the world.
The great paradox that we don't realize today is that the most popular country is Croatia, where it was not possible to go freely until 1989 because it was part of Yugoslavia at that time.
The abolition of visas in the 1990s in the neighbouring countries of the West has led to a huge wave of short-term visits, especially in Austria, to Vienna and Germany.
Czechs could not for a long time travel by air to the west that everyone wanted to see at least for a moment.
For example, in Paris, travel agencies made us Czech women sleep in tents in the parks because our incomes did not allow us to pay for hotel or boarding.
The typical feature of a Czech traveler in those days was to take along his own canned food, sausage, etc... to save money.
Another important moment was the interchangeability of the Czech crown, which allowed our tourists to finally buy Western currency freely after decades.
Our standard of living and average wage have increased, which brought about another important moment around 1997.
Due to the increasing demand for travel, travel agencies have since 1997 started to arrange tours with air charter connections which, through contracts, have greatly reduced costs compared to what was available before.
In the late 1990s, the Czechs had visa-free travel to virtually all the developed countries of the world, except the EU, which later made it easier for us to travel.
Another interesting moment in the post-revolutionary tourism history was when the first air charter to an exotic country, Thailand, was prepared from the Czech Republic.
Since this year, direct air charters have taken Czech tourists to distant warm countries; this winter there will be 12 exotic destinations from the Czech Republic.
That's more than 100,000 Czechs who visit exotic countries every year!
Another interesting moment in this period that symbolizes our post-revolution development came in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the EU abolished visas for Czech tourists and allowed our country to fully fit into the group of developed countries.
In 2008 also, for the first time in history, the Czech people spent more than half of their holidays abroad (50.3%) and for the first time in history spent more than 15 000 CZK per person for holidays abroad including related costs.
