A book shows which pool you can experience the most well-being in.
When Iris Meder went on a research trip for the last 18 months, there was one item that should not be missing from her luggage: her swimsuit.
Lying on her back in the water, she watched the artfully arranged domes, and swam against the Putten marbles that were waiting for her on the other side of the pool and couldn't help but marvel at the meticulously restored Art Nouveau of these converted pools.
If she liked a covered pool, she would write in her notebook all the interesting details about the type of construction and the history of the building.
More than 200 swimming pools have been surveyed in this way by architectural historian Meder and she presented them in her already published book: "Badefreuden" (Bath Joies).
She has led her "tours to the most exceptional baths in Central Europe" in 13 countries.In addition to Germany, Austria and Switzerland, she visited places in Italy, France, Czech Republic, Slovakia, Slovenia, Hungary, Romania, Poland and a city in Luxembourg, Serbia and Croatia.
The 46-year-old German is a true enthusiast of the culture of the bath.
Meder, explains that she doesn't have much interest in sports but he feels attracted to the water in a totally different way.
It is irritating that swimming fans have to settle for blue tiles and the stench of bleached water while joggers breathe the enchanting scent of spicy forests or can listen to the chirping of joyful birds in the park.
"I wondered one day why swimming pools must always be so ugly", said the Viennese.
"So I started a collection of beautiful baths".
The water surface doubles the architecture
A dip in a pool and the sauna oils - the well-being factor in the swimming rooms are huge because all the senses are awakened, according to Meder.
And if the builders had put in a little more effort, the swimming pools could be a real eye-catcher: "Instead of a floor, we have a surface of water in the swimming pools".
"It is transparent on one side, but on the other side it reflects the beauty of the whole building".
All surfaces are visually presented in two ways: high vaults, multi-colored tiles, trampolines.
The small-format picture book "Badefreuden" makes an interesting 190-page report on the history of architecture and culture on the oasis of historical well-being - it certainly makes you want to take a leap into the blue.
Collector Meder discovered some remarkable specimens during her research in Hungary.
Alongside splendid wellness baths such as the 100-year-old Széchenyi bath in Budapest, she found nitrate-containing waters in a natural cave in the karst (cave bath in Miskolc-Tapolca) as well as a thermal bath whose pools are filled with water containing alkali and (Városi Termálfürdö in Jászberény) and located in a bottle-shaped building.
The outdoor heated pools in Switzerland and Austria, on the other hand, offer spectacular views of the city, while the snow-capped Arlberg can be seen from the roof of the bath in Zurich, and the outdoor pool in St. Anton has a window that allows you to see the action on the ski slope.
Perhaps the most extraordinary pool design awaits swimmers in Längenfeld: The Aqua Dome Ötztal looks like a UFO that has just landed in the Alps.
In winter, steam rises from the three open plateaus, while in the background the Ötztal mountains rise to the sky.
The Alhambra in the Black Forest
The smell of bleach doesn't come from every pool in the Meder collection.
Many thermal baths give off a sulfur smell, the Árpád-spa in the Hungarian Bekescsaba gives off a strong petroleum smell, which is hard to believe, to be in a healthy spa.
The smell comes from the therapeutic alkaline waters containing hydrogen carbonate that are almost black and its slime sticks to your skin as soon as you let yourself slide into the pool - a special spa experience.
Iris Meder's search for beautiful pools also suffered disappointments: When she wanted to visit Bad Luhatschowitz, a free outdoor pool in Czechoslovakia, she found herself in a barricaded area.
The bath designed by architect Dušan Jurkovic in 1902 was meanwhile closed.
Looking out of the window of the red-white-yellow Art Nouveau building, she observed the weeds growing between the tiles.
She observed the opposite effect in a lovely swimming pool in the Black Forest: the Bad Wildbad Spa Palace.
The building has already survived three phases; not only can one discover neo-Roman elements that have come out since its design in 1844 but also an Alhambra-style Moorish room that was added in 1900.
Since its careful modernization in 1995, the thermal palace has remained the favorite bath of pool expert Iris Meder - and not just because she is from the Black Forest.
"It is a fine achievement to combine such different building styles into such a formidable unit", says Meder.
With such a palace, a dip in the thermal pool is apparently only a minor issue.
