The German bank examines in detail commodity speculation
By Christian Teevs
Does the German bank give up its speculation in commodities?
SPIEGEL-ONLINE reports that Ackermann has commissioned a task force to study the effects of speculation on the world's poor.
In January, the leader of the group wants to draw the consequences.
- Hamburg - What is it ?
For the citizens of the Federal Republic, the situation is clear: according to a survey, 84% of Germans find it unacceptable that banks speculate on commodities such as maize and wheat.
Two thirds of the people surveyed even demand that German banks and other lending institutions stop doing this because it adds to the problems of the world's poorest.
This is the result of a Forsa investigation into the order of the consumer organization Foodwatch.
The study is based on a report presented by Foodwatch in mid-October.
The author Harald Schumann points out in this article that the speculation of the stock exchanges on global commodities, pushes prices up and that the banks share a complicity in the world famine.
The consumer protection campaign is aligned in practice against the head of Deutsche-Bank, Josef Ackermann, even if the big banks like Goldman Sachs or Morgan Stanley act in the same way.
Speculation on commodities was originally introduced to protect merchants from price fluctuations.
But most experts now agree that the gamblers have become detached from supply and demand - and profit at the expense of the very poor.
Ackermann responded to the criticism differently from the American competitors: He promised to investigate the reproaches and said, "no business is worth risking the good reputation of Deutsche Bank".
According to SPIEGEL ONLINE, an international working group is currently investigating the allegations made by Foodwatch-Report.
The review is to be completed by the end of the year, after which the results of the review are to be presented to the board of directors of Deutsche Bank - usually with recommendations.
At the end of January, the head of the bank will indicate the consequences to be drawn.
This could result in a reduction of the raw material market or even a complete abandonment of the market.
Ackermann builds his image
Foodwatch chief Thilo Bode welcomed the news, but at the same time confirmed his criticism of the financial sector: "The speculation on rising food prices shows in a particularly draconian way how badly the banks of today are hurting the public interest".
Ackermann is the first bank lobby to be particularly restricted today.
"Deutsche Bank must remove from its portfolio all investments for which money has been invested in food speculation", Bode said.
"It doesn't matter to Mr. Ackermann whether it's about the hungry people or whether the reputation of Deutsche Bank is at stake".
Ackermann's realization may at first sight seem surprising, but it is clear that the CEO of the group wants to present a perfect image, a few months before leaving his duties.
Deutsche Bank announced on Monday that the Chairman of the Board of Directors will not change anything in the Board of Directors' plans.
It could improve its brand image with a break from controversial agricultural speculation.
And any losses he might have, he doesn't have to worry about that - his successor will take care of it.
One in two would terminate their commodity investments.
Foodwatch is trying to keep the pressure on the Manager.
So far more than 30,000 netizens have already joined the campaign of the organization.
Bode published the survey on Tuesday, with which the Forsa Institute conducted questionnaires on 1001 people on 7 and 8 November.
Only 11 per cent thought it legitimate that Deutsche Bank offers investments for which food prices bets are made.
Many of the bank's customers would also be personally affected if they learned that their bank was involved in such operations: one in two would, following the survey, terminate all investments for which money is injected into commodity speculation.
43 per cent would advise others not to use such a bank, 49 per cent said they would consider closing their account in order to change banking institution.
21st house in Vienna
The Pavilion That Moved
♪ I'm not sure ♪
A story of architecture with highs, lows and a happy ending: the Austrian pavilion for the 1958 Brussels World's Fair won awards, was a museum in Vienna, remained empty and then fell into ruin.
Now it is open again and serves as an exhibition house.
If one is enthusiastic about post-war modern architecture, for its clear forms, glass hangars, bold and vivid layouts and new building materials which are typical of the belief in technical progress, then the pavilion of the Austrian architect Karl Schwanzer for the Universal Exhibition in Brussels in 1958 is a good and famous example.
The Schwanzer Pavilion was once awarded the "Grand Prix d'Architecture" for its lightweight, suspended steel and glass construction.
The building is considered to this day an important milestone in contemporary architecture.
He made the architects so famous, he also built the Pavilion for the following Austrian Universal Exhibition.
With its legendary BMW four-cylinder house and its adjacent bowl-shaped construction in Munich, it finally became internationally famous in 1973.
His pavilion project as a temporary construction had been exhibited after the Universal Exhibition in the Swiss Garden at the Vienna South Station, was transformed, and in 1962 a 20th century museum opened -
But the building was neither physically nor technically suitable for a museum -- no walls to hang the art, so not a good environment.
However, it was used for a long time, until the contemporary art received a new building in Vienna.
Since 2001 the building has been empty and has become increasingly dilapidated.
Now architect Adolf Krischanitz has transformed the Pavilion, it now bears the name "House of the 21st Century" and will in the future be used as a museum for contemporary art.
On Tuesday evening the Belvedere Museum, to which the house belongs, opened its first exhibition - a stroke of luck in every way.
The new departure was carried out by Agnès Husslein-Arco, who became the new director of the Austrian gallery Belvédère in 2007.
Husslein-Arco, promoted an art historian to a considerable career among others in her youth as a figure skater, then at Sotheby's, at the Guggenheim Museum and as the founding director of the Salzburg Museum of Modern Art, she has particularly carried out transformation work with politicians and the protection of monuments, she has obtained public and private funding and established the exploitation.
Apart from contemporary art, works by the sculptor Fritz Wotruba whose foundation bears the same name have been exhibited there, a café and a bookshop are located there, and an office is to be built there.
Strict supervision, small budget
For the film, Krischanitz was the ideal interpreter.
Not only because he had transformed and sensibly enlarged the Secession of Joseph Olbracht and won the competition, but because he had studied at the Technical University of Vienna and for him the pavilion was "an extremely important place" where he had seen the exhibitions "practically every weekend".
He knew the original design, and he knew the problems of the building, which lost in generosity and lightness following its move to Vienna and by its change of use.
The current transformation had major problems: the building was "an energy sinkhole", says Krischanitz.
The window profiles of the glass facades were changed, insulating glass reinforced with fibreglass was laid and the roof replaced with special safety glass.
The beams of the thermal bridges were strengthened or replaced, and the asbestos-filled roofs were rehabilitated.
Two basements have made room for the new farm, a dimmed light panel between the house and the road provides lighting, a bridge leads to the entrance - it's almost a new construction, but still the light Schwanzer Pavilion.
The original exterior doors remain, the house is painted in a red-brown rust-protective shade.
And the movie theater is exactly the same as it was before.
And all of this under the close supervision of the monument authorities and on a small budget.
"Often good and cheap materials were to be found, and these also please the office of monument protection", says Krischanitz and he draws attention to a rough floor in the basement.
Despite all the stresses, problems and transformations, the building remained flexible and light.
This would have been difficult with the Pavilion, "which came from Brussels", Krischanitz said recently, a typical "Drop-in-the-City" story.
Such architecture is "always in the wrong place" and yet it wants to "awaken the good conscience".
But in this case the 21st century house is not in the wrong place, because if it is a stroke of luck of urban construction: around the Jardin Suisse stands precisely the "quarter of the central station" just newly planned, with offices and apartments.
And another stroke of luck may be happening: the 21st century house could benefit from the addition of another Krischanitz building, because the collector Francesca von Habsburg has bought the temporary art center in Berlin, and as it is said, she is already negotiating with the city to get a site in the neighborhood of the Swiss Garden.
