The scandal bank of Lake Zurich
The most adventurous bank in Europe is not in Italy or France, but in Switzerland.
UBS almost went bankrupt in the financial crisis and it's been skating from crisis to crisis.
It's a German who has to lead now.
It's certainly not what Axel Weber had in mind.
After his spectacular departure from the Bundesbank, it was revealed in July that he would take on an almost as spectacular position in 2013: Chairman of the Board of the Swiss bank UBS - a big step towards an unexpected and lucrative career.
Axel Weber publicly celebrated Switzerland for its beauty and UBS for its newfound solidity and made pleasant remarks about future colleagues.
"UBS has made the Turnaround".
"I look forward to working with Kaspar Villiger and Oswald Grübel".
And yet, as early as September, it was clear that everything was going to change.
A UBS securities dealer in London had hijacked all of the bank's security systems and swindled about 1.7 billion euros.
The chairman of the board of directors of UBS, Oswald Grübel, a well-known banker not only in Switzerland, had to leave.
The chairman of the UBS board has been considered sick for some time - and everyone is asking: When will Axel Weber finally return?
We have already heard that Weber can be a bank adviser from February 2012.
And he will take over as chairman of the board in May - not in 2013, as the bank announced on Tuesday.
For Axel Weber, it is becoming difficult.
He's not a banker, much more an economics professor and bank president, and he certainly would have needed a period of adjustment.
He then suddenly assumes responsibility for the strategy of a bank which has just proved once again that it has long since earned the title of 'Europe's biggest scandal bank'.
Indeed, UBS is on one side huge - until recently, it was the largest asset manager in the world, and on the other, it has been skating from scandal to scandal for years.
Nothing seems to spare the proud Swiss bank.
It started during the financial crisis.
Until 2007, UBS had an excellent reputation.
The image of the Swiss asset manager, quiet and solid, but also cunning, was combined with ambitious objectives: it also wanted to become a very large bank in the field of investment banking.
So UBS on the one hand hand hand handled $1.6 billion more money from wealthy customers in 2007 than any other bank in the world.
On the other hand, it had moved up as an investment bank into the league of the world's largest banks.
It made an impression.
Former banker Hans Geiger, who later taught banking for many years in Zurich, says: "I always took UBS as a model of good banking for my students".
"In the current world, we're asking ourselves, how could I have been so wrong?"
He was deeply mistaken.
In 2007 it appeared for the first time that something was not right at UBS.
In the middle of the year President Peter Wuffli, who had hitherto been regarded as a leading intellectual and a brilliant banker, unexpectedly retired.
A few months later we got a feeling of why he had left.
The bank division had been burned with sub-prime documents and had to make a cross of billions.
To supplement this, UBS announced a capital increase of CHF 13 billion and made a mark on it.
It has indeed found investors for this, but not long before they would have frowned: a non-transparent Asian sovereign wealth fund from Singapore and an Arab sovereign wealth fund, which was kept silent, to the point that we never even heard its name.
It was only the first blow.
In April 2008 it got worse.
The bank was again to report billions in losses, the chairman of the board of directors Marcel Ospel, who was still the second highest paid board of directors in Switzerland in 2006, resigned.
In October 2008, the catastrophe followed: UBS was, due to its investment errors, in the financial crisis before the bankruptcy and had to be rescued by the State.
The national bank bought tens of billions of problematic securities from UBS, the Swiss Confederation gave six billion francs for bonds convertible into shares, for which it could become co-owner of the bank.
All of Switzerland was shocked - for it noted how dramatic it can be for a small country to harbor such large banks.
Finally, the 2007 balance sheet total of UBS was more than five times the economic performance of Switzerland (see graph).
"We have failed to save UBS once again", says bank researcher Geiger.
After the first disaster, the second followed.
A few months before, UBS had already capitulated to a tax dispute with America and declared itself ready to publish the data of wealthy clients, who had cheated the tax perhaps with the help of the Bank.
In addition, it has agreed to pay $780 million in unjustified profits from these transactions, plus a fine.
So UBS pretty much publicized that it had helped with the tax evasion.
At the same time, she lost something that had always been her capital in competition with wealthy clients: the prestige of discretion.
After the scandal, Swiss banking secrecy was never the same.
This was followed by the withdrawal of the head of the board of directors and the chairman of the board of directors.
And the exodus of the money of the clients.
Thus, in a few months, the bank had lost its credibility in the two main business sectors: investment banking because of bad speculation and asset management because of aid to tax fraud.
And, as there was a bit of a return to calm, and as it was thought, that UBS would get away with it, followed by this unfortunate story of securities dealers: a single securities dealer flames 1.7 billion euros, before the bank noticed that something was wrong.
And they publish: with risk management in investment banking it still doesn't seem to work.
"In the Adoboli case, we found that the control of risk has changed too little", says Martin Janssen, an economist and professor of finance at the Banking Institute of the University of Zurich.
The chief financial officer of a major German bank is convinced that "the problem with UBS is that it does not have control of the risks".
However, it was exactly the idea of prudence with which the Swiss bankers had long taken up their function, that of becoming the guardian of the world's great fortune: not too great risks, but security for money - and the world could well collapse beyond the Alpine republic.
The treasuries of the Swiss banks had become a symbol of unwavering reliability as Lindt and Sprüngli are for a particularly noble chocolate.
The UBS headquarters in Zurich still goes hand in hand with the solid cliché of the Swiss private bank - it is only a little larger.
It's a classic situation.
The Bank is based at Zurich Central Station, which leads directly from the central station to Lake Zurich, itself surrounded by the snow-capped peaks of the Swiss Alps.
The buildings here are prestigious, and the rents of the shops are among the highest in Europe.
Jewelers like Tiffany's, you can find them here among the Swiss tradition shops as well as those of the Sprüngli confectionery.
For centuries Swiss bankers have resided here: from the National Bank to the Credit Suisse Palace to elite private banks like Julius Bär.
We enter the lobby of the UBS through a heavy door.
Inside, the walls are covered with marble, in front are thick leather chairs, and next to the bank's logo, a large label for "safe".
UBS knows what the client is looking for here: security.
This idea of the Swiss bank has at some point or another led to market failure - or betrayal of the two big Swiss banks, UBS and Credit Suisse, as the head of a small Swiss private bank finds.
He would rather not read his name in the newspaper, after all like all Swiss bankers he also does business with the two big banks.
The UBS had become too big, he said - especially in investment banking, where the Anglo-Saxons had become more prevalent.
The Swiss would have no say in it.
"And yet they have long since adapted to the Anglo-Saxon ways".
It was the Anglo-Saxon investment bank that changed UBS, made high profits and then the debacle: no European financial institution has lost as much money in the subprime jungle as the great Swiss bank.
The disaster became apparent on October 15, 2008.
"This Wednesday the coalition government of the small country of seven million people has undertaken the largest rescue operation in the history of their nation", writes author Lukas Hässig in his book "The UBS Crash".
With up to 68 billion francs, or 45 billion euros, politicians have agreed to save the big bank from bankruptcy.
How could this happen ?
If you talk to Swiss bankers, they see the problem mainly in the size of UBS.
In June 1998 two of the three largest Swiss banks joined together to form a huge group.
A bank was set up, which was already too big for the small Switzerland - and it kept growing.
What helped was that the two different predecessors of UBS were complemented: a rich but sluggish bank with its strong asset management in Zurich and a poorer but already more strongly internationalised bank.
Suddenly, the international investment banks had favorable access to a lot of money, with which they could spin a huge wheel.
Two names are associated with the rise of UBS: Peter Wuffli, from 2001 to 2007 Head of the UBS group, and Marcel Ospel, former chairman of the board of directors.
"I always thought that Wuffli and Ospel were a dream team", says bank researcher Hans Geiger.
"Wuffli, the great intellectual, who is modest and well versed in models and statistics, and Ospel, the intuitive, who worked his way to the top with the apprenticeship of the bank".
But Ospel would have trusted Wuffli to the end.
And Wufli would have probably made a decisive mistake at the end: "He thought his models were reality", says Geiger.
"This is a tragic fall".
Tragic, perhaps, but not for long.
One thing is clear: the exuberance came before the fall.
The staff at UBS clearly remembers the executive meetings at which the head of the Wuffli Group always used the same slogan: to dethrone Goldman Sachs.
The Bank of America was the most powerful investment bank on the planet.
She commissioned the "League Tables" rankings, which documented the banks' success at that time.
After all, UBS wanted to go all the way.
