Peter Englund's new book is deep and generous, and it's called "The Beauty and the Sorrow: An Intimate History of the First World War", and it opens with a long list of characters that make you cringe.
A tip to start with: carefully tear this page and make it your bookmark.
In this novel by Peter Englund, this list of characters will be your GPS, a beacon during those few moments when, as one of his men or women, you will be troubled and desperate in the fog of war.
Peter Englund is a Swedish historian and journalist.
He is also the new permanent secretary of the Swedish Academy, which awards the Nobel Prize in Literature.
He wrote an unusual book that he accurately describes as "anti-historical".
It contains a few well-known names, important treaties, or famous battles; there are hardly any ambassadors or discussions of strategies and equipment.
It is not so much a book about what happened, he explains, but a "book about what it could be like" and it contains "feelings, impressions, experiences and moods".
"Beauty and the Sorrow" sums up the wartime experiences of 20 more or less ordinary men and women, from both sides of the war, from young schoolgirls and botanists to climbers, doctors, paramedics and salesmen.
Some of them will become heroes.
Some will lose limbs, go insane, or lose their lives.
Their lives are wavering here like the candles of a church: as some are extinguished, new ones are being rekindled.
Peter Englund's book deviates from the traditional history books.
It refutes the idea that World War I was merely a terrible trench war on the Western Front.
"Beauty and the Sorrow" aptly describes other theatres of war: the Alps, the Balkans, the Eastern Front, Mesopotamia and East Africa.
The soldiers in this book are under beehives; one is spending Christmas in Egypt under the pyramids; tsetse flies are an intractable problem.
This book is moving from the first page.
War invades these people's lives like a natural disaster, like Hurricane Katrina that stinks of cordite.
When gunshots are heard in the distance, and you are a stay-at-home mother, do you stay or run?
Who's coming anyway?
Almost no one can understand what happened, or even the reasons for this war.
Englund writes, "the lack of facts has been compounded by speculation, hope, fear, fixed ideas, conspiracy theories, dreams, nightmares and rumors".
"Beauty and the Sorrow" follows individuals such as Florence Farmborough, an English nurse in the Russian army, as well as Richard Stumpf, a young sailor in the German High Seas Fleet.
Their stories are mainly drawn from memoirs, letters and other documents already published.
Their versions of life can be terrifying or exciting, but are best preserved by the accumulation of small moments and isolated details.
Most of them deal with deprivation and the ability to cope.
In telling the story of a German schoolgirl, Peter Englund writes: "Ersatz, everywhere ersatz".
"Replacement coffee, fake aluminum, fake rubber, paper bandages, wooden buttons" - that's what I thought.
He's pursuing the alternative food in Germany.
He describes "meat made from cooked rice crushed in sheep fat (and finished with a fake wooden bone); tobacco made from dried potato roots and skin; wooden shoe soles".
He states that "837 authorized meat substitutes are registered in sausage production.
Some stories are about honor and courage.
A U.S. man acknowledges his own drive for savagery and says of war: "You feel that after all, that's what men were meant to be, rather than sitting in a comfortable chair with a cigarette and a whiskey in your hand, reading a newspaper or a best-seller, and pretending that such a veneer is synonymous with civilization, and that there is no savage behind your thick, stubby shirt.
On the other hand, a British soldier realizes that he is in danger of dying, and no one will notice or pay attention to him.
"When you are resigned to sacrifice yourself, you hope to have an audience", he wrote.
Unfortunately, it is more like "a condemned man strangled in secret".
Other observations concern the decline of an old Europe and new types of terror.
"The conflict is increasingly becoming a story of economic competition", writes Peter Englund, "a war between factories".
He captures the arrival of what he calls "a new species in the bestiary of the turn of the century: the well-articulated and ideologically convinced mass murderer, in well-fitting clothes, who carries out his butchery while sitting behind a counter".
People act in unexpected ways; there are as many basic behaviors as there are heroic ones.
Peter Englund tells of soldiers who tried to catch a venereal disease from prostitutes at any cost in order to avoid service at the front.
"The most grotesque expression is found in the trade of pus due to gonorrhea, which soldiers buy and spread on the genitals in the hope of ending up in the hospital", he writes.
"The most desperate apply it to their eyes, resulting in blindness for life".
In this Swedish translation by Peter Graves, Peter Englund's prose is supple but not ostentatious, perfectly suited to his task of humanity.
In dozens of short scenes, he captures how the war "triggered forces that were entirely uncontrollable: extreme nationalism, social revolution, anti-religion".
People are starting to wonder why their leaders are waging war against them.
The best books dealing with the First World War are often indirect, such as Paul Fussel's Great War and Modern Memory, or Erich Maria Remarque's Nothing New in the West, rather than complete.
Peter Englund's work is an unconventional pantheon.
The ending of the book is the most overwhelming ending I've ever read in a work of non-fiction.
I won't tell.
But it's as if he's emerged from his book, holding in your hands that page with the list of people and burning it with a match.
