Walls have eyes: researchers are studying you on Facebook
Before he became the new face of the far right in Europe, Anders Behring Breivik was just a guy sharing his anti-immigration views online.
On Monday, Breivik, who admitted to being caught in a murderous rampage in Norway in July that left 77 people dead, faced his first trial.
While Breivik acted alone, he was far from being in cyberspace: he had spent much of the time before the attack on his computer, chatting with a few million nationalists who support far-right groups on social networking sites.
After this summer's tragedy, researchers are eager to learn more about these people.
But how can we find them?
Easy... log in to your Facebook.
"We realised that it was not that hard to find them", says Jamie Bartlett, lead author of a recent report by the DEMOS thinktank on digital populism in Europe.
Facebook is full of so much personal information, Bartlett says, that researchers could simply use the site's advertising tool to find the people they're looking for with scientific precision - the way marketers have been doing it for years.
Jamie Bartlett's team found that half a million members are fans of far-right groups in Europe, and they targeted them with ads, but instead of linking them to a new group or product, the ads invited users to take a survey, asking questions about their level of education, attitudes toward violence, and optimism about their own future.
By connecting with these people through Facebook, Jamie Bartlett and his colleagues were able to interview 10,000 supporters of 14 far-right parties in 11 European countries - without leaving the office.
"It's a new way of doing research", says Jamie Bartlett.
Some of the results are not at all surprising: the online supporters of right-wing groups are mostly men, young and against immigration.
But surprisingly, "those who combine online and offline activism are more reasonable, more democratic and less violent than those who remain behind their computer screens".
The DEMOS study is just one example of how Facebook has become the new go-to tool in the hands of scientists.
Think tanks, medical researchers and political scientists use the site to study all the subjects that touch health issues as well as social trends, through "Likes", wall posts and status updates.
With over 800 million active users adding an average of three pieces of content per day, the "data supernova" is generating an explosion in search, increasing the number of research papers whose name appears in the headline by almost 800% over the past five years.
Some researchers say the beauty of Facebook is that it allows you to study people you wouldn't be able to reach on the street.
"Before, when you tried to do surveys on people in the British National Party, it was very difficult to identify them".
"You were supposed to go to the party, but they would never let you in", says Jamie Bartlett.
"Facebook avoids all of that - you have direct access to their information".
Others say the site could offer a way to identify and treat health and social problems.
According to a recent study by Dr. Megan Moreno of the University of Wisconsin-Madison and colleagues, young students who talked about their achievements on Facebook while drunk were significantly more likely to be alcoholics than students who were quiet about it.
Megan Moreno suggests that fellow students, such as counselors, could monitor the site and intervene to possibly help a student whose status would be too often about alcohol.
"You can't treat a problem if you don't diagnose it", says Dimitri Christakis, co-author of Megan Moreno and director of the Center for Child Health, Behavior and Development at the Children's Research Institute in Seattle.
"We know how to identify children at risk, who would otherwise be unrecognized".
Facebook also constantly accesses its users' information.
The site's data team studied statistics on love life and Valentine's Day, the turnout in the 2010 midterm elections, and a national happiness index (using only available information - champions of digital freedom have long argued that the site could make its treasure trove of data available to others for research).
But Facebook users know that the site is watching them, whether they like it or not - in exchange for being able to play Scrabble with a friend who is thousands of miles away, the site is allowed to access your information.
But what happens when Facebook users are part of a survey that they haven't even heard of?
While researchers have well-defined guidelines for how to gather information other than via the Internet, it is a different story online.
"I don't think a lot of users have ever thought about a researcher studying their profile", says Neil Selwyn, a sociologist at the London Knowledge Lab, referring to a 2006 study he conducted of his students' Facebook walls.
"As far as they knew, the exchanges were only seen by their friends".
Then there is the question of methodology.
Even without going online, there's no guarantee that the subject of a study is completely honest.
On Facebook, it is impossible to know the degree of truth of a profile or on a user's wall.
"What you say on Facebook and what you do in real life are two totally different things", says Neil Selwyn.
So despite his experience as a technology researcher, Neil Selwyn thinks a notebook and a pen are still the best tools you can use.
