At four different points during the interview, the answers come a long time after the questions - between 10 and 15 seconds of reflection, during which Steve Jobs weighs his thoughts clearly, in order to provide a precise answer.
We also find moments where Steve Jobs' perfectionism resurfaces, where he seems eager to hear Cringely's questions, giving him elbows to get him to speed up and move on to questions or topics of greater importance.
Filmed before the age of Pixar, the iPod, the iPhone, there's a strangely prescient aspect to Lost Interview, where Steve Jobs assesses what he considers good and bad about other companies and shares his own vision for the future of computing.
It's one thing to read the posthumous evaluations of Steve Jobs' career, but there's something raw and inspiring about the man we see here, the anxious dreamer on the eve of greatness.
He has a vision of how things can and should be.
He explains them and then immediately applies them.
Here's a quick recap of seven remarkable sequences from Lost Interview:
On how he learned to run a business:
"All these years I've been asking, 'Why do you do things?' and the answer is always the same: 'Oh, just because you have to do them.'"
Nobody knows why, nobody thinks deeply about things in a company.
That's what I found out.
Steve Jobs goes on to give details of his efforts to simplify accounting at Apple.
Perplexed as to how costs were recorded - one often starts with a "standard cost" assessed at face value, then adjusted with a "variation" - he developed an automated factory that guaranteed accurate calculation of commercial costs.
On the opportunity to play a trick on the Pope:
Steve Jobs tells the story of the "Blue Box" he created with Steve Wozniak - a device used to hack into phone networks and make free long-distance phone calls.
The device has been the subject of much writing beforehand, but the euphoria of Steve Jobs here in his description of the Blue Box as an act of appropriation is contagious.
He describes how he and Wozniak tested the box by using a public telephone, making a call and then connecting from one AT&T network to another while bypassing as many satellites as possible.
"We would wrap the ball around different things half a dozen times and you'd scream into the pay phone and it would come to you a minute later on the next pay phone", Jobs explains with a laugh.
"We were young and thanks to this Blue Box, we learned that we could create something ourselves that could control billions of dollars of infrastructure around the world".
We didn't know much about anything, but we were able to invent something small that could control big things, and it was an incredible lesson, and I don't think Apple would have ever existed without it.
Steve Jobs goes on to tell of a wonderful trick he and Wozniak came up with: he telephoned the Vatican with the Blue Box in the middle of the night posing as Henry Kissinger and asking to speak to the Pope.
As several members of the Catholic hierarchy are summoned in the middle of the night to speak to the American diplomat, the two accomplices go on a rampage of laughter just before the Pope himself is awakened.
On his love of technology (and Bill Hewlett's outing):
At the age of 12, while hunting for spare parts to make a frequency meter, he looked up Bill Hewlett's number in the yearbook and called him.
Shortly after their 20-minute conversation, Steve Jobs gets a part-time summer job at Hewlett-Packard.
"It had a remarkable influence on me, it was the only company I had seen at that age and it shaped my definition of a company and the way employees are treated".
Steve Jobs later became one of the HP employees to visit the company's research labs in Palo Alto, where he discovered the "first desktop computer ever designed".
It was the size of a suitcase, had a little cathode ray tube in it, and I fell in love with it.
The teenager I was went back to HP and started writing programs for this machine.
On improvising with innovation:
Several times in the interview, Steve Jobs talks about inventing new products on a whim.
Early in his career, as he was settling down to sell a few printed circuit boards, he was asked by a client to assemble a complete computer.
Working on only 30 days' credit, he had to take care of the assembly and delivery of the finished equipment.
Later, at Apple, he recalled the difficulties he had in developing a computer mouse:
"I remember big fights... people were yelling at me that it would take me five years [to make a $300 mouse]. I got tired, I went out and I went to a designer".
Ninety days later, we had a mouse that we could make for $15 and that turned out to be incredibly reliable.
About the big companies that are out of breath:
Long before he revived Apple, Steve Jobs had foreseen the way many industry leaders would go wrong and lose control of their market share.
"Suppose you worked at IBM or Xerox, you made a better copier or a better printer, what next?"
You have a monopoly on the market, so the company is not more successful.
Sales and marketing can drive it, so [these are the types of people] who end up running the companies and the product-specific staff are left out of the decision-making.
The product engineering that has led to this monopoly position is completely corrupted by people who can't imagine designing a good product versus a bad product - the manual labor required.
That's what happened at Xerox...
Xerox could have owned the entire computer industry.
It could have been 10 times bigger than it is now.
They took defeat for victory.
On innovation as an art form:
"A huge amount of manual labor separates a brilliant idea from an outstanding product... as you develop that idea, it changes and grows".
You learn a lot about its subtleties.
There are trade-offs to be made... some things you can't do, electrons can, glass, robots, factories too.
You have to keep thousands of things in mind (these concepts) as you put them together.
And finally, the decisions are made by personal taste, and it's about trying to expose you to the best products that humans have created, and trying to bring those things into the product that you create.
Picasso once said that good artists copy and great artists steal.
We're always ashamed to steal great ideas.
And that's part of what makes the Macintosh exceptional, because the people who worked on it were musicians, poets, zoologists, historians, who just happened to be the best computer scientists in the world.
If it weren't for computer science, they would have done extraordinary things in another field.
Scalia and Thomas dining with health care law opponents as the court convenes
On the day the Supreme Court is sitting in camera to consider the political dissent question of whether opposition to President Obama's health care law will be heard, two of its justices, Antonin Scalia and Clarence Thomas, were spotted at a dinner sponsored by the law firm that will defend the case in the high court.
