Mr Nag said the eurozone crisis risked causing "significant repercussions" across Asia.
BASD's forecast of 7.5% economic growth in Asia in 2011/12 now faces "risk of loss" due to the European threat.
He noted that vulnerable emerging markets needed to develop "rescue plans" to protect themselves from economic upheaval and significant capital outflows.
Pentagon warnings of potential defense cuts
Defense Secretary Leon Panetta ramped up pressure on Congress Monday, warning that impending automatic budget cuts would undermine national security, triggering a financial chain reaction from the corridors of the Pentagon to the battlefields of Afghanistan, to the rallies of civilians.
The Pentagon is already digging into $450 billion in spending cuts for the next decade, but now fears that an additional $600 billion or more in cuts is imminent if Congress fails to reach a spending agreement.
"The impacts of these cuts would be devastating to the department", Panetta said in a letter to Senators John McCain, R-Arizona, and Lindsey Graham, R-South Carolina.
He said that Congress's failure to reach a budget agreement resulting in what is known as sequestration, would result in 23% cuts as well as the freezing of many new projects.
"Such a large cut, applied so indiscriminately, would render most of our ships and construction projects unfeasible - you cannot buy three-quarters of a ship or a vessel - and seriously undermine other modernization efforts", Panetta writes to senators.
"We would also be forced to part with a number of our civilian staff and because the reduction would be imposed so quickly, we would almost certainly have to send civilians on unpaid leave in order to achieve the goal".
"These changes would shake the faith of those who support our military and seriously damage our preparedness".
The reductions would eventually affect combat troops, Panetta continued.
"While wartime financing of overseas contingency operations accounts would not be directly affected by the sequestration, wartime efforts would be negatively affected by severe disruptions in core budgets", Panetta warned.
"Contracting staff would be reduced, resulting in delays in contracting and overseeing contracts that support the war".
"Staff handling salaries would be reduced, causing delays in payment to war suppliers, and legal and political support would be disrupted".
Both senators had written to Panetta 10 days earlier, asking for details on the potential impact of the automatic cuts on the Department of Defense.
"The consequence of a sequester on the Department of Defense would have triggered a rapid decline of the United States as the undisputed leader of global military power".
"We are fiercely opposed to this draconian action", the senators said in a joint statement Monday afternoon upon the publication of Panetta's letter.
"It's not a consequence we can live with, and it's certainly not one we should impose on ourselves".
"Seizure is a threat to the national security interests of the United States, and it shouldn't have to happen".
Whether Panetta's letter and recent warnings from senators increase pressure for a budget compromise or a call to exempt the Pentagon from cuts remains to be seen.
Panetta has been increasingly blunt about possible cuts, even as he himself has risen to the top of the Pentagon with years of budget expertise in Congress and the White House and the knowledge that he was faced with tough choices.
At a press conference last week, the secretary of defense painted a bleak picture of what could happen - a military with a shell, but no core.
"It's a ship without sailors".
"This is a squad without bullets".
"This is a fighter plane, with not enough trained pilots".
"It's a paper tiger, an army of barracks, buildings and bombs that don't have enough trained soldiers capable of carrying out the mission", Panetta said in his opening remarks at the Pentagon.
"It is a depressed force, ill-prepared and unable to face potential adversaries".
"De facto, it is inciting aggression".
In an addendum to his letters to McCain and Graham, Panetta specifically stated how further cuts could "generate significant operational risks: delayed response to crises, conflicts and disasters; severe limits on our ability to deploy and engage in the world; and unacceptable assumed risk in future combat operations".
And Panetta said that some of the biggest defense projects could go under the knife, including those already tested and some just in the early planning stages.
This list included the Fighter F35 Joint Strike, a planned new bomber, the next-generation ballistic submarine, the new littoral combat ship and the new field vehicle, which would replace the Army and Navy's Humvee.
Stopping development and testing of the F35 could generate $80 billion in savings over 10 years, but its supporters say it's a critical step in improving and responding to potential threats from China and other rivals.
How to Spot a Lie
A look at recent headlines reveals just how pervasive deception and lying are in everyday life.
Republican presidential candidate Herman Cain is busy trading allegations of sexual harassment with multiple women; each side accusing the other of lying.
Penn State administrators have been accused of perjury for allegedly covering up reports that a retired football coach sexually assaulted boys.
Last week French President Nicolas Sarkozy was caught on an open microphone telling US President Barack Obama that Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu was a liar.
Lies have destroyed careers and convulsed countries.
New York congressman and Internet celebrity Anthony Weiner, was made an idiot by quickly issuing denials contradicted by irrefutable evidence.
Former presidential candidate John Edwards has been charged with campaign finance violations related to the cover-up of an extramarital affair.
And then, none of us who have lived through history will ever forget the media circus that President Bill Clinton set in motion by lying during his second term about his sexual involvement with Monica Lewinsky.
There are many reports of cheating on school and college tests.
There have been cases where teachers have given test answers to students in order to get a good look at their performance evaluations.
Mentors who should teach the opposite send the message that lying and cheating are acceptable.
How much deception do we encounter ?
Studies show that on any given day, you can hear anywhere from 10 to 200 lies.
In fact, many of these are pious lies.
Another study found that strangers lie to each other three times in the first 10 minutes of their first encounter.
Detecting or spotting lies is an essential skill that everyone must acquire, for both personal and professional reasons.
Far from being a board game, like, say, charades, where the goal is to shout, "I got you", cheating detection is a serious branch of knowledge based on scientific data collected over the last six decades from prestigious universities that have conducted in-depth research on such projects, particularly in psychology and physiology.
One of the results of the research is that the oldest myths about lying have been debunked.
Liars look you in the eye.
They don't always stammer, blush, or fuss.
Do not conclude that liars are difficult to detect and hard to uncover.
A trained lie detector can discover the truth by examining the structure of the statement, the micro-expressions of the face, the question formation and the time of response.
I've spent several years examining scientific findings in the vast and ever-emerging body of knowledge about deception, and it's clear that deception detection is a modern skill that's easy to learn and useful for navigating our complex world -- especially if your professional responsibilities include hiring, interviewing, negotiating, or managing.
Good liars are good at reading other people, putting them at ease, managing their own emotions and intuitively detecting how others perceive them.
We know from research that extroverts lie more than introverts, that men lie more "self-centered" lies while women lie more "other-centered" lies - usually to protect someone's feelings - that married people lie less often to their partners than unmarried people (but that the lies they tell tend to be huge).
We also know that if you're perceived as a disbeliever, others will feel less guilty about lying to you.
How can you tell if someone is lying?
First, observe the normal behavior of your subject.
This is called "establishing the reference data".
This helps to provide a reference point for measuring subsequent changes.
Notice your subject's posture, his laugh, the quality of his voice.
You need to know if someone is normally moving their feet all the time so that you don't make unfair accusations when you see them moving their feet in the middle of the meeting.
Then look for signs of verbal and nonverbal deceptive behavior.
Consider these clues as red flags, not evidence of deception.
People who are deluded may freeze their upper body when trying to remember their story, they may point their feet toward the door, lean toward an exit, change their posture significantly, or present a post-interview relief - an exaggerated sigh of relief, a change in posture when all the tough questions are over.
Interviewers often falsely indicate that the interview is over just to try to trigger the post-interview reaction.
So pay attention to the vocabulary of your subject.
The famous Scott Peterson slipped by using the past while pretending his murdered wife was alive, triggering a national search to find her.
Deceptive individuals may also use distant language: "I did not have sexual relations with this woman... Ms. Lewinsky" or repeat a difficult question entirely.
The most common verbal cues are subtle.
One may use a lot of "wood tongue" in answering a difficult question: "Well... to be honest... if I remember correctly... to my knowledge".
This makes the response perceptive rather than factual and is often a red flag.
There is no magic formula for detecting lies, but developing the skills to recognize deception is possible.
These skills will improve the chances of anyone avoiding being victimized by scammers in their professional and personal lives.
