The economic impact of the adverse climate
During the first year of Mario López Valdez's administration, unemployment and informality increased in Sinaloa, foreign investment decreased and the economy contracted.
2011 is a year that will be remembered in the economic history of Sinaloa, it is the first year of the Government of Mario López Valdez, self-called of the change, which generated great expectations regarding the progress of the economy, but given the climatic adversity of the beginning of the year, the rise is not observed, in exchange there is a deterioration of the main indicators of economic development.
February's low temperatures, besides causing trillion-dollar losses to the agricultural sector, limited the state's economy's opportunities for growth, caused a contraction in overall economic activity by 3.6% in the first half of the year, mainly due to the historic 31.16% drop in agriculture, which affected the dynamism of other economic sectors.
According to the report of frost damage issued by the Mexican Council for Sustainable Rural Development, there was damage of 582 million 835 hectares cultivated, of which 78.03 percent suffered total damage and the rest 21.07 percent suffered partial damage, the main crops affected were vegetables, corn and chickpeas.
The decline in economic activity generated, until November, a steady rise in unemployment in the state, according to the National Institute of Statistics and Geography the state unemployment rate during the first three quarters of the year was observed an accelerated increase, because while from January to March 55 thousand 053 Sinaloens were unemployed, with a rate of 4.53 percent of the Economic Active Population, in the second quarter the rate became 5.28 percent and from July to September the average continued to rise to 6.19 percent, a rate that represents more than 74 thousand Sinaloens unemployed, an increase compared to the first half of 18 96 thousand people.
Less liquidity
Unemployment in Sinaloa during the year is multifactorial, according to economist Gerardo López Cervantes, director of the Faculty of Economic and Social Sciences of the UAS, the increase in unemployment can be explained indirectly depending on the actions carried out by public policy.
"What we are seeing is a rise in unemployment that is due to various factors, including the loss of liquidity in the market due to a restriction of resources by legislation passed in Congress to combat money laundering, because for people who earn dollars in an illicit way it is not easy that they work to earn them, they invest them and use them in something", he said.
Migration detained
López Cervantes pointed out that the increase in unemployment is also due to a demographic factor.
"The number of people leaving the state to go to work abroad, in the United States, has been restricted, first because of the difficulties of entering and second because when they enter they already have a lot of difficulties in finding work, these people stay here and ask for sources of work, which causes unemployment to rise", he said.
Lack of seriousness
The analysis of the Sinaloan labour market is aggravated by the high level of lack of seriousness that prevails among the working conditions, according to INEGI, 60.38 percent of the population employed in this state work without contributing as a worker to any social insurance institution.
Apart from unemployment and lack of seriousness, another reason for the state's disconnection are low wages, the entity has the lowest salaries in the country, according to the records of the Mexican Social Insurance Institute and the Secretariat of Labor and Social Provision.
The average monthly income of Sinal workers was, until September, 5 thousand 352 pesos, much lower than the national average, which stands at 7 thousand 375 pesos.
Contraction of IED
Apart from the decline in economic activity and the rise in unemployment, 2011 saw the biggest drop in Foreign Direct Investment in the last 10 years, according to the Secretariat of Economy from January to June, the State FDI reached 630 thousand 697 dollars, which represents a decrease of 87.74 percent compared to the 5 million 143 thousand 312 dollars recorded in the same period of the previous year.
In turn, the Secretariat of Economic Development of the State Government records a total investment of 17,280 billion pesos per year, recorded mainly by companies in the tertiary sector.
The debt
Given the scenario of economic contraction, the State Government in July requested the approval of a credit of 3 billion pesos, for investment in infrastructure projects in the 18 municipalities, with the aim of reactivating the economy, the approval of the State Congress was 2,600 billion pesos and until November there was no benefit from the debt in any sector of the state economy.
