Court upholds "analogical cutting" in Mexico in 2015
The replacement of analogue signals with digital is one of the most important changes the world has suffered in recent years.
The Supreme Court of Justice of the Nation (SCJN) has rejected the constitutional controversies that the Senate and the House of Representatives have formulated against the presidential decree that advances the so-called "analog cut" from 2021 to 2015, as the eight votes needed to invalidate it were not obtained.
A minority of four ministers, including the President of the Court, Juan Silva Meza, considered that President Felipe Calderón did not exceed his powers when he issued the decree detailing the actions to be followed to make the transition to terrestrial digital television a reality.
With this result, the constitutional controversy promoted by the Senate of the Republic was defeated for not having reached the qualified majority of eight votes for the Court to rule on the constitutionality or unconstitutionality of the decree, and this continues to be in force.
The draft sentence, drafted by Minister Olga Sánchez Cordero, proposed declaring the decree unconstitutional, due to the fact that the regulation of radio and television is a legal attribution reserved to the Federal Telecommunications Commission (Cofetel), in contravention of the principles of hierarchical subordination and reservation of law.
In favor of the project only voted Zaldívar, Jorge Mario Pardo, Margarita Luna and Sánchez Cordero himself.
With this argument, both the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies promoted two constitutional controversies to challenge the decree and by admitting the complaints, Minister Sánchez Cordero suspended the application of the decree and all the actions provided for by it for the digital transition.
The plenary session of ministers also decided to reject the complaint lodged by the Chamber of Deputies, without discussing the project for which Minister Sánchez Cordero is also responsible.
In his speech, the Minister President said that he did not agree with the arguments of the bill, in the sense that the Federal Executive could not structure through general standards the measures for the public administration to prepare for it.
"I also do not believe that doing so would affect the autonomy of the regulatory body", he said, and he recalled that the planning of public policies in strategic areas such as the telecommunications sector is the responsibility of the Federal Executive, whose constitutional mandate is to run the state.
The replacement of analogue signals by digital signals is one of the most important changes the world has undergone in recent years and this has resulted in better use of the radio spectrum, better signal quality and more channels.
Postponing the change, he argued, would be postponing the benefits of digitisation which implies a public interest decision that is not just a technical one, "because it also includes economic, social, political and national security issues".
The Commission's proposal was to be adopted by the Council of Ministers on the basis of a proposal from the Commission.
He recalled that a large number of countries around the world have already completed the digital transition and they have done it through the Executive, despite the fact that they had highly specialized technical bodies.
The executive, he said, could not be said to have invaded the sphere of competence of the Congress by issuing the decree in question, since it ensures the respect of laws issued by the legislature in the administrative sphere.
The possibility of a vote-by-vote count in Michoacán is being analyzed
According to the data highlighted by PREP, the difference between the first and second place in the election of the governor is only 27 percent, even without counting the votes corresponding to 879 of the total 6 thousand 74 minutes.
The possibility of a vote-by-vote count is a reality in the electoral process this year in Michoacán, where according to the data provided by the Preliminary Electoral Results Program (PREP), the difference between the first and second place in the election of the governor is only 27 percent, even without counting the votes corresponding to 879 of the total 6 thousand 74 minutes.
In this sense, the president of the General Council of the Electoral Institute of Michoacán (IEM), María de los Ángeles Llanderal Zaragoza, recalled that a few days ago, on November 9, the electoral body approved a series of guidelines to harmonize local standards with the federal electoral reform.
It will be recalled that Michoacán has not approved either its Political Constitution or its State Electoral Code or its Electoral Justice Law, at the same time that the State Congress approved the reforms shortly before the end of the legal period for this electoral process to take effect and Governor Leonel Godoy Rangel omitted its publication within the deadlines stipulated by the Law of the Official Journal of the State, with the argument that he had some objections.
On the same day, the Supreme Court of Justice of the Nation (SCJN) resolved the constitutional controversy promoted by the local Legislative Power and qualified as "invalid and illegal" the vote of the state representative for the constitutional reforms, because he does not have the right to "sanction or challenge them".
Interviewed on the possibility of "vote by vote", María de los Ángeles Llanderal said that with the approval of the corresponding guidelines by the General Council of IEM it will be possible to carry out the partial and total counting of votes by the local electoral body.
For example, the partial counting of votes for one or more electoral packages may be due to: the results of the minutes not coinciding; there is no ballot paper and the counting in the ballot box file is not with the president of the ballot box; or there are obvious errors or alterations in the minutes.
Furthermore, the total count of votes received in all polling stations may be carried out where there is evidence that the difference between the candidate who is deemed to have won the election and the candidate who came second in the ballot is equal to or less than one percentage point; provided that there is an express petition at the beginning of the session from the representative of the party and/or coalition who presented the second of the candidates indicated.
The total counting of the votes may also be carried out if at the end of the joint counting it is found that the difference between the candidate who is supposed to have won and the candidate who came second is equal to or less than one percentage point, provided that there is an express request from the representative of the political party from which the candidate came second, in which case the electoral packages which were the subject of the partial counting will be excluded.
It should be mentioned that this is the situation in the Morelia election, where according to the PREP, the difference between the first and second place is only 0.16 percent, even without counting the votes of 129 of the 923 total minutes.
