The new Italian government will be formed on Wednesday
Prime Minister-designate Mario Monti will meet with Italy's president tomorrow to introduce the new government that will face a crisis that has brought the country to the brink of economic disaster.
The prime minister-designate, Mario Monti, will meet with Italy's president on Wednesday to introduce the new government that will deal with a crisis that has brought Italy to the brink of economic disaster and endangered the entire Eurozone.
A statement from the presidential palace announced that Monti, who was appointed on Sunday, would meet with President Giorgio Napolitano on Wednesday to confirm that he can form a government.
He is expected to present a cabinet composed mostly of technocrats, though it is unclear when the new executive will take office.
Monti said he would present the president with the results of his talks with the political parties in his attempt to form a government.
'I want to confirm my absolute confidence in the ability of our country to overcome this difficult phase,' the former European Commissioner told reporters.
Monti did not explicitly say he could form a government, but the tone of his comments indicated that the obstacles had been overcome.
The framework is now well defined, he added.
Monti completed the process to form a government in less than three days, in a shorter time than normal, while Italy is fighting a political and financial crisis that has pushed the costs of its debt to unsustainable levels.
The new administration headed by former European Commissioner Monti must approve a tough austerity package demanded by European leaders to regain the confidence in Italy that had been damaged.
Underlining the pressure on Monti to hurry, market instability has placed the yield on Italy's BTP 10-year bonds above 7%, the level at which Greece and Ireland had to be rescued.
Emma Marcegaglia, leader of the Italian Confindustria union, told the media after meeting with Monti: "We said we would support this government a lot".
We believe that this Government is the last chance for Italy to get out of this emergency.
Monti's chances of success were boosted considerably by the support of Silvio Berlusconi's PDL party, which was forced to resign last Saturday by the crisis.
"We believe that the efforts of Professor Monti will have a good result", said Angelino Alfano, secretary of the centre-right party.
The support of the PDL, the largest Italian party, is significant because until now many of its members had opposed the technocratic majority government that Monti is forming.
Parliamentary support
Monti's new government must have strong parliamentary support to implement what will likely be unpopular austerity reforms.
Any failure or delay in its efforts could lead to a new and devastating attack on financial markets.
The Italian Association of Foreign Banks added to the pressure by observing that a Monti bankruptcy would be a disaster.
Monti began consultations with political parties, trade unions and employers' groups and youth and women's organisations on Monday.
He'll finish his meeting tour Tuesday night.
Monti was appointed on Sunday by Napolitano, who enabled an extremely rapid transition in response to the crisis.
After a brief respite at the end of last week when it was clear that Berlusconi was going to resign, Italian debt costs have now returned to critical levels amid uncertainty over the success of the new prime minister.
Saving Italy, with a public debt of 1.9 trillion euros, would be too much for the current financial defenses of the Eurozone.
Monti said his government should persist until the next elections, scheduled for 2013, despite widespread predictions that politicians will only give him time to implement reforms before moving the elections forward.
Monti said he would like to include politicians in his cabinet, but the major parties insist that it should be formed only by specialists, an indication of their objections to a process forced by financial pressure.
Political sources have reported that mutual distrust and disagreements between parties make it difficult to attempt to include political figures.
