Quinteto includes the country in its turn to celebrate two decades of trajectory
"Going to Costa Rica is a dream come true"
In an exclusive interview with Viva, Pearl Jam bassist Jeff Ament said the band is ready to deliver one of their best concerts yet next Sunday at the National Stadium.
They have waited for more than 20 years, but the band assures that for them it will also be a dream come true to perform in this country.
It's that bassist and founding member Jeff Ament made sure of, speaking exclusively with Viva from Brazil last week.
The band is on the South American leg of their two-decade celebration tour and on Sunday 20 will make their only stop in Central America.
That day will be at the National Stadium, starting at 7:30 p.m., next to the group of Los Angeles The X and the national of Las Robertas.
This is an excerpt from the conversation, the full transcript of which can be found in La Nación on the Internet.
For Costa Rican fans, the fact that Pearl Jam will be performing in Costa Rica is a dream come true.
Going to Costa Rica is a dream that has come true for us too.
This is our second time in South and Central America and so far it's been great.
I've only been to Costa Rica once for a vacation; it's such a beautiful country and I think we can spend a few days there.
So we're really excited to take our music out there.
I ask you, because there's a kind of devotion to the band, the fans live with intensity the days before.
What is your message to your most ardent followers?
Thank you for sticking by us all these years.
It took us 21 years to get to Costa Rica, and we thank you for waiting so long and we are sorry that so much time has passed until this concert.
Some people are already saying that his concert is the biggest show of the year.
Does that add a little pressure to your visit?
Some of the biggest shows we've done in the last 21 years have been in the last two weeks.
We played two huge shows in Sao Paulo and we hope that this will help us get in shape for this concert in Costa Rica.
We're really looking forward to it.
We love this country, we love surfing and the jungle, and for both, Costa Rica is one of the best countries in the world.
How did you discover Costa Rica and its surf waves?
We have a lot of surfing friends and I have a very good friend who lives in Tamarindo and the waves are incredible there.
My friends always went surfing in Costa Rica, and Nicaragua, right next to Mexico, is a great place to surf, and that's how we learned about it, through the guys who like to surf.
When you see the tour, you've seen huge shows, with lots of songs.
What are you planning for your presentation in Costa Rica?
Since we have never been there, we have no restrictions as to what we can do.
We're going to try to do the best show possible, with a wide variety of songs; we're going to try to perform two songs from each album and offer our fans a good and diverse repertoire.
You never rehearse the repertoire.
What is the reason?
I think part of the reason is that we have nine records and we can play over 120 songs and everyone likes different songs, which is why it's very difficult to choose which songs to play at each party.
When we have two or three songs in our repertoire that we haven't played for a very long time, it helps us stay focused and it surprises us because it reminds us of why we loved those songs and that we may have forgotten.
It makes the show more interesting for us and therefore I think it also becomes more interesting for people.
With this tour, you're celebrating 20 years of trajectory.
Looking back, is it hard to believe all that you've accomplished?
Yes, I'm sure you are.
First of all, I don't think any of us ever imagined that we would be a big rock band, and the fact that we've been doing it for over 20 years makes it sound like a dream.
We continue to share our blessings and the fact that we can continue to make music together is very moving.
We love each other and we love making music.
We're lucky to be able to go to places in the world that we've always wanted to go.
Things couldn't be better for us.
What does it mean to you to have been a fundamental element in the creation of grunge?
It has always been an honor for us to be part of this group of large groups.
We're very friendly with the people from Soundgarden, Mudhoney and Alice in Chains.
It's surprising when a movement arises from a group of friends and it's unusual.
Every once in a while, a group comes out of a city, but it's much more bizarre when five or ten groups come out of the same city at the same time.
We are proud and honored to be part of the Seattle group.
We still play with some of them from time to time.
Last year we did a festival with Alice in Chains and we went to Canada with Mudhoney, we saw Soundgarden on their tour, so we're lucky to still be friends with all of them and it's an honor for us to be a part of that Seattle sound that has emerged.
It's also very strange that a group like yours has been able to stay together and with the same members for so long.
Yeah, the four of us have been together for 21 years and Matt (Cameron) joined us 13 years ago, and only that's a lot longer than a lot of bands normally last.
First of all, I think we're all lucky to be alive, and second of all, we all care about each other.
We're all close friends and because of that there are musical boulevards that give everyone the freedom to experiment.
We have trust in each other with each other's music and it couldn't get any better.
Your relationship with the word celebrity has not been easy; however, thanks to your success, you have been able to do what you want.
How do you find a balance?
As we grew older, it became easier for us to find a balance.
We make sure we don't spend too much time on the road because it's easy to fall into this game of big crowds and people who love your music.
Remembering that people are here for the music helps us to remember that we have to respect the music and what it has brought, without thinking about the fact that we are famous and a rock star, which none of us really cares about.
How do you remember your other project, Mother Love Bone?
I think we wrote some good songs and it was great at first.
We were a band for almost three years and we didn't release a record until after Andy (Andrew Woods) died.
There was a lot of frustration about how short it was and the most important thing is that we're still very good friends with Bruce (Fairweather) and Greg (Gilmore) who started in the band with us and when I listen to a song or I see a picture I think about the amazing person that Andy was and how he made me laugh, it was always a pleasure to work, laugh, talk about music, football and many other things with him.
He was an amazing human being and we miss him.
The national group Las Robertas will open the show in Costa Rica.
Is it true that you know his work, especially Eddie Vedder, and that's why you chose her for the opening?
Yes, the production has sent us videos with different proposals and this was the band we liked the most, so we are looking forward to seeing what Las Robertas can offer live and it must be very entertaining.
Why do you always change the lyrics of Yello Ledbetter live?
This is a question for Ed, so I don't know.
He sings it, and I think he does it with the first words he can think of.
As a bass player, what are his influences?
There are so many...
Some of the first people I remember were Geezer Butler, John Entwistle, C.J. Ramone, John Doe, Paul McCartney, Chuck Dukowski...
There are so many influences, I could spend the whole afternoon talking about the bass players I love.
How did Pearl Jam manage to keep grunge going despite the fact that it's out of fashion?
I think we all feel a little disconnected from the word grunge.
When I think about it, it reminds me of the bands I just mentioned, like Mudhoney, Soundgarden, Nirvana and all the others that came out around the same time, and if that's relevant now, I think that's wonderful, because it's music that's worth listening to and bands like Mudhoney are now making better music than ever.
At first, his music had a more obscure content and now it has become more positive.
What is the reason for this change?
And that's interesting, because I think there are songs on the new album that seem lighter, but there are also songs, like The End or Just Breathe, that are described as very dark songs, even though they may sound a little positive.
With both of them, when Ed played them for me, I cried when I listened to them and these are deeply obscure songs.
