Park or mountain?
Architects agree on the appropriateness of the call beyond the controversy over fees
The municipal competition on the 16 gates reopens the debate on the role of Collserola in Barcelona
In the mid-1980s, at the height of the already defunct Metropolitan Corporation of Barcelona (CMB), this Administration printed posters promoting Collserola.
The brochure described the mountain as the great park of metropolitan Barcelona.
It also contained a numerical comparison with New York's Central Park.
With the demise of the CMB in 1987, the park became once again, in the imagination of many people, the upper limit of Barcelona, the Catalan capital being the only one that does not orient itself on the north-south axis, otherwise high (mountain) - low (sea).
The qualification of Collserola as a natural park is in favour of this idea.
The reference was no longer Central Park but Yellowstone, with wild boar as the Yogi bear.
This was the situation until, in September, the town hall called a mega-competition consisting of 16 contests for all the access gates to Collserola.
A doorway to the park, no doubt.
That's it, or someone wants to put doors on the field.
The question arises: Collserola - park or mountain?
The competition, both in terms of its organisation and in terms of reflection on the city, is a topic of conversation for all architects in Barcelona.
It's almost a recurring theme that two members of this ancient caste of elected officials talk about when they recognize each other in an elevator.
And this is just one of the few opinions that coincide with three architects from Barcelona, university professors, who presented themselves.
Miguel Roldán, Daniel Modol and Marta Bayona: the competition is timely.
Roldán said that after tackling the coastal front, "it is necessary to discuss the mountain front" because the speech by Ildefons Cerda, that of the green blocks, has not been completed.
"We must assume that the largest park in Barcelona is the beach.
Among other things, it is very accessible.
The title 'Collserola gates' contains a 'lexical trap': they should not be thought of as accesses to a park, but as the delimitation of certain areas in which to act".
Modol, like Roldán and Bayona with experience in the urban planning world, described the proposal as an "intellectual challenge" with "some dangers".
The dangers arise from the "uncertainty of the projection of public space" after the experience of the 1980s in the area of the Forum "swan song".
The first fear is the very delimitation of the boundaries on which we can build.
"To limit something means to set the next step", that is, to go beyond it.
"We need to think about new urban planning instruments, because the current ones [referring to the General Metropolitan Plan (PGM) ] can cause real disasters".
Modol, who is more specific, thinks that, in a simplified way, the slope of the El Valles de Collserola region "can be understood as a park, not that of Barcelona".
Modol recalls that there is already work done by the Patronat of Collserola that "should not be lost", thanking the opportunity that the town hall offers to his corporation to intervene in this project "from the first moment".
He also believes that the proximity of the mountain to the city is the safe-conduct for architects to enter the debate, but he doubts whether this technical profile should lead the multidisciplinary teams ("all a success", he says) that have to be created: "We, the architects, should be only an instrument".
Bayona insinuates that the answer to the question which gives the title to this piece is complex, because the basis of the competition lacks a global vision of Collserola: "Sixteen transversal competitions have been called - he says - in the mountain-sea direction, but there is no longitudinal reading that sees and understands the area as a whole".
This means that, at least in this case, he has chosen to participate in all 16 competitions.
In another way, a project so that one of the doors can clash in the program and definition with that of the architect of the next door.
In his opinion, yes, the City Council should ensure that the strip immediately above the Ronda de Dalt should be provided, throughout its extension, with a zone of equipment that makes a smooth transition between the city and the green.
