Secretary Dionisio Pérez Jácome gives details of the plane crash in which the Secretary of the Government, Francisco Blake and seven other people lost their lives
The Secretariat of Communications and Transports (SCT) reported that the results of the accident in which the Secretary of Government, Francisco Blake Mora and seven other people lost their lives, indicate that the helicopter crashed directly into the ground with complete structural integrity, without the pilot being able to attempt a forced landing.
During a press conference, Dionisio Pérez Jácome, Secretary of Communications and Transportation, mentioned that before the aircraft took off, the pilot found that the weather conditions were adequate for flying.
"Elements that appear to indicate the unit had various contact with the ground, blades made contact with trees at 25 meters where the unit lost the fuselage".
He also informed that the unit was designed for 19 people, therefore it met the requirements necessary to transport the staff.
Furthermore, he said that the investigations made in the impact zone do not report the appearance of pieces on the ground.
"In one search it was reported that there are no parts or components of the aircraft in another place, the impact was structural.
"The helicopter was designed for 19 passengers and met the requirements for carrying them.
The ground was tilted from seven to 30 degrees.
For the moment, the Secretary assured that a priority is to have the results as soon as possible; but the investigation can take a few months, it can even take a year.
Gilberto López Meyer, general director of Airports and Auxiliary Services, said that at the time of the impact, the helicopter of the Presidential Staff was operating at cruising speed and it happened on a gentle ascent.
"This information supports the hypothesis of normal cruiser operation at the time of impact", he says.
During the press conference, the head of the SCT, Pérez Jácome, listed six important elements in the investigation:
Visual flight:
According to the aeronautical regulations, the flight was performed according to the rules of visual flight, which implies that the crew must have visibility during the flight and on the ground.
Weather conditions:
Reports in the AICM mentioned adequate conditions for takeoff, and as the aircraft advanced toward the border area between DF and the State of Mexico there were low-altitude layers of fog.
Selected routes:
It is likely that due to the foggy conditions the crew searched for a lower altitude area with more visibility towards the Cuernavaca Valley.
Location of impact.
The coordinates of the impact and the last record of the aircraft on the radar coincide, probably before the impact there was no loss of control or alteration of the flight path.
Dispersion of aircraft debris over a small area:
The information available so far suggests that the impact occurred on a straight and sideways trajectory.
The model of dispersion of the remains of the aircraft allows to assume that the helicopter struck the ground in conditions of structural integrity.
No fire or explosion was detected.
At the crash site there is still no trace in the remains of the aircraft of any type of explosion or fire.
The latest results from the investigation indicate that the aircraft had multiple ground contacts.
During the field work, parts of the aircraft were found at an altitude of 9,200 feet above mean sea level, with the ground sloping from seven degrees to 30 degrees of inclination.
The photographs show the sequence in which it possibly disintegrated along its journey.
The information provides evidence that appears to indicate that the helicopter may have had multiple impacts with the ground.
After a thorough search of an area wider than the surrounding area, no scattered parts of the aircraft were found, supporting the presumption that the impact occurred in structural integrity.
MSS announces protocol to find the gene of obesity
Social insurance is leading an investigation to discover the gene of obesity in children and young people; this is supported by IPN specialists
The Mexican Institute of Social Security (IMSS) announced that it is conducting an investigation to discover the gene of obesity in children and youth, called the 'Genetic Protocol of Child and Adolescent Obesity' which will allow to have the markers associated with overweight.
In a statement, the head of the Medical Research Unit in Biochemistry at the Hospital de Especialidades of the National Medical Center of the 20th Century, Miguel Cruz López, explained that a multidisciplinary team of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social workers had been formed.
This team is supported by specialists and postgraduate students from the National Institute of Public Health (INSP) and the National Polytechnic Institute (IPN) Centre for Research and Advanced Studies (Cinvestav).
The survey invites the public, whether eligible or not, to attend the participating sports units of the IMSS in Valle de México, where the tests for minors are carried out every Saturday from 8:00 a.m.
He stressed that the protocol started in the Cuauhtémoc Sports Unit (Estado de México Poniente) and that from October 8, the activity takes place in the Nezahualcóyolt Sports Unit (Estado de México Oriente).
After reaching the target of 500-600 miners, the study will continue in the Independencia Sports Unit (southern Distrito Federal) and finally in the Morelos Sports Unit (northern Distrito Federal).
He explained that the aim of this investigation and that of the other is to know the components and the importance of genetics in the development of obesity and to identify risk factors in Mexican children and young people to prevent the onset of chronic degenerative diseases.
He mentioned that the aim is to bring together three thousand children and young people between the ages of six and 14, with the consent and under the supervision of their parents, for the application of the specific nutrition questionnaires.
They will also be asked about their physical activity and their family history of inherited diseases, to avoid risk factors that trigger conditions such as diabetes or kidney failure.
He explained that on Saturdays all participants will be subjected to anthropometric measurements (weight, height, waist circumference), blood pressure, glucose, triglycerides, cholesterol and insulin levels and genetic tests (they are trying to identify people associated with childhood obesity).
Cruz López reported that this investigation is the result of the concern of health professionals for the alarming weight gain in the case of minors.
"The 1999 and 2006 health surveys reported that in just six years there has been a 77 percent increase in obesity in boys and a 47 percent increase in obesity in girls; there has also been a dramatic increase in overweight", the IMSS specialist said.
He said the justification for the search for markers is based on the fact that the country's population is different from others by its genetic history.
He reported that on average, Mexicans have 65 percent Indo-American heritage, 30 percent European and five percent African heritage and this condition is reflected in people associated with diabetes and overweight.
He explained that the genetic basis for obesity is usually the inability to burn the excess energy (calories) that is consumed, which is stored as fat.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit for the participants is the integral evaluation of the children, which allows to detect whether they have a degree of overweight or obesity.
He even says that the presence of dark-colored pleats (acanthosis) on the neck and forearm indicate the likelihood of suffering from metabolic abnormalities and even pre-diabetes.
The information is handled confidentially, doctors give it to the parents in writing, and they are told every step and lifestyle change they need to take to prevent disease.
Cruz López explained that there are three main components that cause overweight, obesity and other chronic conditions: sedentary lifestyle, which is lack of daily physical activity, sitting for most of the day in front of the TV and using transportation instead of walking short distances.
Another cause is the high caloric intake, i.e. the higher consumption of sugary drinks, carbohydrates (tamales - meat paste with corn flour wrapped in corn leaves), bread, pizza, hamburgers, etc.) with a high content of fats and proteins and the genetics analyzed in this protocol.
UNAM's asphalt would prevent the rain
Rafael Herrera, researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry of UNAM, develops asphaltes modified with polymers to produce a mixture with a better yield, irrespective of environmental and temperature conditions
If the signs of the pavement were resolved, it would no longer be necessary to repair about 200,000 waterfalls each rainy season in the Valle de México Metropolitan Area, warns Rafael Herrera Nájera, researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) of the UNAM, who assured that if the process of construction and maintenance of the bituminous pavement is adequate, the waterfalls could be reduced or even eliminated completely.
During his conference "A Technological Opinion on Slate", organized as part of the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that his laboratory is developing asphaltes modified with polymers to produce a mixture with similar characteristics to asphalt, but with greater mechanical resistance, both at high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nájera felt that this type of modified asphalt could be used in places where the climate is extremely hot, such as some cities in the north of the country, to improve yield, and therefore, the formation of cassis.
He explained that asphalt, the heavier part of petroleum, is a set of hydrocarbon molecules, molecules with a heavier molecular weight, called asphaltenes, and molecules with a lower molecular weight, called malthenes, which together give the pavement its characteristic viscoelastic behavior.
The viscoelastic behaviour of asphalt is that at high temperatures, close to 180 degrees, it behaves like a liquid, at 120 degrees C its viscosity is very high and at 50 degrees C it is almost solid, while at very low temperatures asphalt becomes brittle, he added.
This means that the strength of the asphalt on the streets is not uniform and changes during the day according to environmental conditions and temperature, warns the chemical engineer.
The FQ researcher observed that the streets of Ciudad de México in their majority were covered by a flexible paving, composed of six layers of materials, the last three of which involve asphalt.
The outermost layer is the asphalt layer, which consists of small stones bathed in asphalt and later compacted.
Each of the small stones that make up the layer, he pointed out, is bathed in asphalt.
When vehicles pass through it, generating forces, it allows the forces to spread very well in the pavement.
If we had modified asphalt, these would spread better, the chemical engineer thought.
On the asphalt layer, he says, they put a last layer called the rolling layer, made of fine stone, that is, sand, which is also bathed in asphalt.
As this is the layer in contact with the wheels of vehicles, it must have more mechanical strength than the asphalt layer and provide adhesion in the road.
As the part of the pavement that receives and distributes the forces, the rolling bed also requires that it be of adequate thickness and the material of which it is made must be clean.
Climate, especially humidity and temperature variations, are also very important factors to consider, especially water, he says, as these greatly affect the yield of the asphalt layer.
When the soil becomes wet, water spreads inside the layer and it's hard for it to come out, which softens all the layers of the pavement and therefore causes the blackheads.
In the process of forming a cassis, he says, the first thing to go bad is the bearing film and only later is the asphalt layer affected, but the damage does not take place immediately, but it is a process that must be treated at the first signals with adequate maintenance programmes.
The member of the National Research System explained that vehicle load is another important factor in the formation of undercarriage and therefore the thickness of each layer of pavement must always be related to vehicle load and ensure its satisfaction, to avoid frequent formation of undercarriage.
Rafael Herrera warned that there is still much to be investigated and worked on asphalt, for example, bituminous emulsions, which in other countries already exist on the market and allow the repair of the cassis easily and without the need to use high temperatures.
