So was the work of the person from Cali who identified the body of Alfonso Cano
A typist from Cali went down in history as the man who confirmed the death of "Alfonso Cano".
The work of these officials is crucial.
On November 4th, a typist from Cali's CTI went down in history as the person who confirmed the identity of the FARC supreme leader, "Alfonso Cano", by comparing his fingerprints.
Of the seven typists who work in the local offices of the CTI, this week it was the turn of Eliazar González, a Puerto Tejada man who has been working in the field of criminal investigation for 21 years.
At the beginning of his career, González worked in the municipalities of Chocó, where many times he had to spend more than five days in the forest to get to the place where the bodies were to be identified.
In the year 2000 he transferred to the capital of Valle and after taking adequate courses, he specialized in dactyloscopy, which is the study of friction skin, that is to say the palms and feet.
During the week of the operation against alias Alfonso Cano, Eliazar was warned to take with him clothes for at least three days.
Something very big was waiting for him.
On Friday night, he left for Cauca in a helicopter from Palmira.
He knew he had to identify two bodies and that one of them was suspected to be that of the man who led the oldest guerrilla in the world, so he was asked to take the card with the ten fingerprints of Guillermo León Sáenz (his real name).
But when he arrived with the investigation team at the body site, he did not recognize it by its physical appearance, because it was very different from what he had seen in the media.
He had no beard, he was dressed like a local peasant, without glasses and much thinner.
But the prints don't lie.
Accompanied by a Galton magnifying glass, ink, a scanner, and a flashlight, Eliazar compared the corpse's fingerprints with those on the map.
His eyes did not deceive him: it was "Alfonso Cano".
That same night, the Puerto Tejada man was the official who confirmed to the Minister of Defense, Juan Carlos Pinzón, that he was the supreme leader of the FARC.
Searching for the Fingerprint
For a typist from Sijín de Cali the recognition that President Juan Manuel Santos gave to Eliazar González, in a press conference for the operation against "Cano", is very significant.
A lot of people don't know our work.
Dentistry is an exact science, with no margin for error, which can be crucial in solving crimes.
Aside from identifying bodies, fingerprint technicians support investigations for crimes such as robbery and homicide and confirm the identity of captured individuals.
When caught, many offenders present false ID or have no documents.
We take their fingerprints and run them through the database.
The researcher related that in a burglary he had to remove part of a wall of a house, for in that place the thief had pressed his hand to take out a safe full of jewelry and money.
"The walls are difficult because they are not adequate surfaces to take a fingerprint, but in this case we were able to get the fingerprint of the whole hand and identify the offender who had participated in different robberies", he recalls.
Fingerprints can also rule out or confirm suspects in homicide cases.
A man was recently found dead with bottles of liquor around him.
Through the investigation, it was determined that a relative may be a suspect in the crime and indeed a print on the bottle coincided.
While that doesn't guarantee he's the killer, it does place him at the crime scene.
A CTI fingerprint technician explained that "fingerprints are extracted from objects with chemical or physical reagents".
When they appear, a lift or a tape is used to remove them.
Afterwards, the prints are sent to Asif, the criminal database, or the National Civil Registry.
"The problem is that there are still many Colombians without papers", said the ITC expert.
He explained that not everything is as it is shown on the television program CSI.
Just as all that glitters is not gold, not everything you touch becomes an imprint.
It can be used, however, if the necessary confrontation is made.
