Japan Rebuilding After the Earthquake
GDP up 1.5% on domestic consumption, ending downward spiral from early March
Since March, Japan's economy has been paralyzed, still recovering from the devastating earthquake that turned into a nuclear crisis, the country's worst disaster since World War II.
The Tokyo Government's initial estimates put the damage at $300,000,000, a figure which, despite the difficult world situation, seems to have been alleviated.
After three consecutive quarters of decline, the data on Gross Domestic Product between July and September were used to turn the page for good: GDP increased by 1.5% compared to the previous quarter and by 6% at an annualized rate.
The second quarter growth rate - for the Japanese, the fiscal year begins in March 2012 - also represents the highest growth rate since the January-March 2010 period.
The recovery is partly explained by the resumption of equipment acquisitions to restore areas devastated by the earthquake and subsequent tsunami.
In fact, firms increased their investments by 1.1%, compared to the 0.9% decrease in capital expenditure observed from January to March, the first decrease after six months of uninterrupted growth.
However, the real stimulus for the Japanese economy is not based exclusively on the Keynesian impulse to take advantage of the crisis to consolidate - or rebuild - infrastructure, to use the deficits to grow from scratch.
Japan has awakened mainly thanks to the evolution of domestic consumption, which currently represents 60% of Japanese GDP.
This variable increased by 1%, driven by higher expenditure on vehicles, travel and leisure activities.
