The Social Democrats/Christian Democrats government in Austria decided on Tuesday to inscribe a budgetary "golden rule" in the constitution in order to reduce public deficits and thus avoid a possible degradation by the rating agencies of Austria's sovereign rating (triple A).
The Social Democrat Chancellor Werner Faymann announced this decision after a ministerial meeting, when Austria's public debt was 74.6%, well above the 60% limit set by the Maastricht Treaty, but well below the debts of countries such as Italy, Greece and Spain.
"If Austria's creditworthiness were to be reduced by just one point, from AAA to AA+, we would have to pay three billion euros more in interest each year", argued Christian Democrat deputy chancellor and foreign minister Michael Spindelegger.
Austria is thus responding to a request made at the Brussels summit of the eurozone member countries on 26 October last: the Heads of State and Government had called for the reduction of public deficits and the return to a balanced public accounts to be included in the constitution or in a law of the same value by the end of 2012.
The system adopted by the Austrian Government is closer to the "German model", Germany being the first European country to adopt such a "rule".
By 2017, the structural public deficit will have to decrease by 0.75% of gross domestic product (GDP) each year and, as of 2017, the structural public deficit of the federal state will not exceed 0.35% of GDP each year, while the regional states and the municipalities will have to present balanced budgets.
The objective is to bring public debt under the 60% criterion set by the Maastricht Treaty by 2020/21.
