Energy policy:
Facts must prevail over dogmas
If there is one subject which cannot be dealt with on the basis of short-term considerations or under the influence of emotion, it is energy policy.
The availability and cost of electricity directly affect the purchasing power and competitiveness of firms.
It is right that an election date should provide an opportunity to reflect on such issues and the role of nuclear energy in them.
The debate will only be fruitful if it explores the full economic, social and environmental consequences of the options proposed.
The French must base their opinion on objective facts, rational data.
With seven billion people on the planet, demographic change will double the demand for electricity by 2050, unless we deprive a huge part of the world's population of a vital element.
At the same time, the scarcity of fossil resources will have to be overcome in order to continue producing electricity permanently, not to mention the urgent need to reduce greenhouse gas emissions to combat climate change, a topic that has disappeared from the ecological debate.
The Fukushima accident does not change any of these parameters.
That is why Germany remains isolated in its decision to give up nuclear energy.
This is not the case in Belgium, which submits its own to the need to find a replacement source capable of replacing itself, or in Switzerland, which simply intends to build only the latest generation of power stations.
On the other hand, the United Kingdom, Finland, Poland, the Czech Republic, the Netherlands, Sweden, South Africa, China, India, Brazil, to name just a few, are pursuing their projects with determination.
The United States, on the other hand, decided after Fukushima to add a new unit to its fleet by resuming the construction of a plant that had been interrupted after the accident at Three Mile Island.
The German model, which focuses on renewable energy sources, is sometimes presented as an example, but the reality is contrary to the discourse.
The choice of Berlin will result in higher electricity prices, an energy dependence aggravated by the increased use of imported gas, especially from Russia, and a jump in CO2 emissions caused by the construction of gas and coal-fired power stations.
Within a few months, all these unfortunate effects are already being felt.
The case of Denmark is worth considering.
Europe's champion in wind power, from which it derives 30% of its electricity, it is also one of the largest users of coal and gas due to the intermittency of the wind; as a result, its CO2 emissions and electricity prices are respectively 65% and 50% higher than the European average.
On the other hand, thanks to the consistency of our energy policy, our neighbours pay an electricity bill 40% higher than that of French households.
In a globalised economy, the cost of energy is a key factor in competitiveness and a guarantee of the maintenance of the industrial tool on the national territory, while French companies benefit from the cheapest electricity in Europe.
As a result, any significant reduction in the share of nuclear power would lead to a sharp increase in the price of electricity, which would make the beautiful statements about the reindustrialization of our country and the defence of purchasing power illusory.
The price that a large majority of French people refuse to pay, especially since they do not oppose this energy on principle, the polls show.
It should be recalled that the energy policy of our country has made it possible to build an industrial sector of 125 000 direct jobs and 410 000 indirect jobs.
It is a strong exporter, and this has led to a galaxy of SMEs specialising in international markets and making them very effective job creators that cannot be outsourced.
If France were to decide to withdraw from nuclear, it would sacrifice many of these SMEs by reducing as a burden the 6 billion euros a year of French exports of nuclear equipment and services.
What electrician would order an EPR designed to last 60 years when the manufacturer 's decline is scheduled ?
To solve the energy equation, we must admit that there is no such thing as a miraculous power source, nor is there any evil one.
Areva's development of low-emission, nuclear and renewable solutions is a testament to the complementarity of energy sources.
For the nuclear industry, maintaining the highest level of safety is an absolute imperative.
In France we have a Safety Authority which exercises uncompromising and transparent control over existing power stations, such as the Flamanville site.
Our teams, whose professionalism is recognized, are imbued with the same obsession with safety.
In the past half century, the nuclear industry has suffered three major accidents.
Only one, Three Mile Island, was operated under normal operating conditions and had no human or environmental consequences.
In Chernobyl, the design of the reactor and unforgivable human errors caused the tragedy.
In Fukushima, some seem to forget that the accident was the result of two natural disasters of unprecedented magnitude that caused the death of tens of thousands of people.
The nuclear industry will learn from this accident, as it did from the previous two.
As a result of this approach and cooperation between the safety authorities, the operators and the French and German manufacturers, the EPR has a design that makes it able to withstand such phenomena.
While it is considered by all electricians who wish to build a power station, the halt of its construction in Flamanville would be a magnificent gift to the competitors of Areva and EDF, leaving them free to take the lead in the inevitable development of nuclear power.
It is necessary and legitimate to seek the best energy package for our country, but it would be irresponsible to let emotion, dogmas and partisan maneuvers dominate a debate so decisive for the economic, social and financial situation of our country.
Is immigration a burden or an opportunity for the economy?
The immigration policy of Nicolas Sarkozy has been criticized from various angles - overcrowding of police, judicial and administrative services subject to the policy of the figure, compatibility of this policy with the self-proclaimed status of "country of human rights" of France.
More recently, the administrative harassment of foreign students has made headlines, with the Minister of the Interior (read Libération of May 23) proclaiming that France "does not need foreign talent, bricklayers and restaurant servers".
But it is rarely analysed from an economic point of view.
There is a fairly broad consensus on this issue between the left and the right.
On the right, the tone was set by Jacques Chirac, who declared in 1976 that "900,000 unemployed should not be a problem in a country comprising nearly 2 million immigrant workers", and on the left, by Michel Rocard, who explained that France "cannot accept all the misery of the world" in 1990.
The only difference is the degree of generosity.
In 2005, fear of the invasion of the national territory by hordes of Polish plumbers was shared on both the left and the right.
On both sides, immigrants are perceived as a burden on the French economy and society.
The only difference is the degree of generosity that is shown to immigrants.
In his programme, François Hollande confines himself to banalities, indicating that co-development will solve our "migration problem".
This idea of immigration as a burden, a problem, may be electorally rewarding; it's economically very costly.
As economists Ian Goldin and Geoffrey Cameron point out in a recent book synthesising the latest knowledge on immigration (Exceptional People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Define Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, 352 pp.), there is a broad consensus among experts on the positive impact of migration on economic growth, wages and employment in countries that receive immigrants.
Restricting immigration
Fears about the impact of migrants are based on the idea that they may replace domestic workers, especially the low-skilled, putting downward pressure on their wages.
But experience shows that, in reality, immigrants are much more complementary than substitutes for national employees, working for the most part in sectors where there is a shortage of jobs.
Low-skilled immigrants work in sectors that do not attract domestic workers, and the most skilled in dynamic sectors where training does not keep pace with the supply of jobs.
A positive effect on wages
Just as a surgeon will struggle to work in a country with a shortage of anaesthetists, these complementarities between nationals and migrants mean that the arrival of immigrants has a positive effect on the wages and employment of nationals.
Giovanni Peri has calculated that a 1% increase in migration flows leads to a 0.6 to 0.9% increase in real wages in the long term.
This is without taking into account the fact that the diversity brought by immigrants contributes to the creation of ideas and to economic growth (high proportion of naturalized immigrants among the American Nobel Prize winners; Google, Intel, Paypal, eBay and Yahoo were founded by immigrants).
Migrants are also net contributors to social systems, averaging 1% of the total budget in European countries.
The World Labour Organisation estimates that in Germany, for example, an immigrant who reaches the age of 30 will make a net contribution (revenue minus expenditure) of EUR 150000 to the public budgets on average over his or her lifetime.
At the beginning of his term of office, Nicolas Sarkozy wanted to go after the missing growth points "with his teeth".
The teeth in question, by serving as a deterrent to immigrants, have had the exact opposite effect.
