Nord Stream, new gateway for Russian gas to Europe
The Nord Stream pipeline, which links Western Europe directly to Russia via the bottom of the Baltic Sea, has been put into operation.
It's supposed to provide the gas equivalent of 30 million homes.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, wanted to celebrate the event with glitter.
More than 500 guests, including four heads of state and government, attended the inauguration of the Nord Stream gas pipeline, which links Russia to Germany directly under the sea, on the shores of the Baltic Sea on Tuesday, with a fine buffet and orchestra.
The European Union has also been involved in the negotiations for the conclusion of the agreement on the European gas market, which is to be signed by the European Union and the United States.
With this new pipeline, an additional 27.5 billion cubic metres of Russian gas will be delivered to Western Europe every year via a first 1,224 km pipeline linking the St Petersburg region to the state of Mecklenburg-Pomerania.
A second pipeline is to be completed by the end of 2012, delivering a total of 55 billion cubic metres of gas, equivalent to all of France's consumption.
And there's already talk of building a third one on the same course.
For Gazprom, the timely completion of this massive project looks like a victory.
The project was strongly opposed by Poland and the Baltic states.
Nord Stream will enable gas to be delivered directly to Germany, avoiding any land passage through a third country (Poland or Ukraine).
As a result, both countries lose some of their power: it becomes more difficult for them to put pressure on Russia by threatening to close its access to Western European markets.
At the height of the debate, Warsaw did not hesitate to compare Nord Stream to a "new German-Soviet pact", referring to the 1939 Hitler-Stalin alliance to occupy Poland.
That is, whether the subject is politically sensitive.
Western Europe, by supporting this Russian project, has gained greater security of supply.
But this has come at the cost of weakening energy Europe, since the project has created a rift between Eastern and Western Europeans.
In just five years, Russia has succeeded in achieving its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich Western countries, which are big consumers of gas and whose deposits are in decline.
"This gas pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, it is a new artery that links us in an organic way", confirmed François Fillon when inaugurating this gas pipeline, demonstrating how the major gas contracts are as much political as economic.
All this explains the broad smiles of Gazprom executives, present in large numbers in Lubmin, at the point of arrival of the gas.
The construction of this pipeline is also a technical achievement.
The underwater tube is steel reinforced with concrete to protect it from ship anchors.
It rests on the sea floor, at 200 m in average.
The construction of the dam was necessary to avoid minefields from the Second World War.
"A hundred had to be removed or destroyed as a precaution", says Jens Müller, a spokesman for Nord Stream.
Measures to protect wildlife have also been increased.
The tube is a long metal snake, as heavy as 242 Eiffel towers, that is not interrupted by anything along its entire length: neither valve, nor maintenance station.
A control platform was planned off Sweden, but the project was abandoned as the Swedes were unwilling to see a Russian state-owned company permanently established off their coast.
"If there is a problem, we stop the gas flow in less than a minute", says Jens Müller.
In the event of a leakage, the gas in the gas pipeline is therefore released into the air.
But this is considered unlikely by the builders who have designed the welds to have a leak every 100,000 years.
The pipeline is monitored by a submarine robot, which is towed by a ship for external observation, and by a device which moves inside the pipeline.
It is shaped like a cigar and is inserted into a tube three feet wide and pushed by the gas.
When it arrives, after three full days of travel at a speed of 10 feet per second, it provides precise information on the possible deformations of the metal.
The pipeline was designed to operate for fifty years without the slightest repair.
The circulation of the gas is simply ensured by pressure.
It's 200 bars at the start, 100 at the finish.
Five companies have joined forces to carry out this project.
The leader remains Gazprom, which retains 51% of the shares.
The German companies E.ON and BASF each account for 15.5%, followed by the Dutch Gasunie and the French group GDF Suez (9% each).
The five companies have set up a joint venture, called Nord Stream, to build and operate the pipeline.
The company is headquartered in Zug, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favourable.
Gazprom then leased all the gas transport capacity to this company for a period of 20 years.
"Gazprom will pay for the total capacity, regardless of the amount of gas actually transported", says Jens Müller.
The construction of the gas pipeline was financed by 30% by the shareholders and 70% by bank loans.
The total cost of the work is expected to be around EUR 7.4 billion for the two pipelines.
For example, GDF Suez has invested 240 million.
But the minority shareholders are sure to recoup their costs, since only Gazprom bears the risk.
The pipeline emerges from the Baltic Sea at Lubmin, on a sandy coastline planted with pine trees.
The valves, 15 feet (4.5 m) high, form the gas outlet.
Sensors measure the pressure, temperature and specificities of the incoming gas before it is transferred to the German pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, this terminal has been receiving one million cubic meters of Russian gas every hour that passes.
At full capacity, it will be 3 million per hour and by 2012, 6 million.
Moleskine, a brand name.
Created about 15 years ago by an Italian company, Moleskine is a way to bring back the taste of writing.
It has the smell of adventure, of hours spent writing by candlelight.
The Moleskine notebook is easily recognizable, with its black rectangular cover, its elastic, its leaves of a broken white color, as if aged by time.
Yet, the Moleskine notebook as we know it today was born... in 1997.
The Italian company Modo Modo, based in Milan, decided at the time to launch a notebook design but distinguished.
Maria Sebregondi, then a consultant for the company, was responsible for the launch of the new product.
The notebook is inspired by an ancient production technique, the mole skin, which refers to a varnished cotton used to cover benches, for example.
This type of notebook was very popular with writers and travelers.
"Moleskine has revived an old and forgotten object, which was an icon of avant-garde artists until the 20th century", says Maria Sebregondi, who has since become the brand manager at Modo Modo.
Success is here.
Between 2006 and 2010, sales increased by 26% to 12.7 million units sold.
This is a far cry from the confidential production of the first few years, when only 3,000 notebooks were designed.
Moleskine is exported beyond Italy to 70 countries, from France to the United States.
It is difficult to draw a robot portrait of the buyer, because the notebook is attractive to businessmen, students and professionals alike.
Like Moleskine, its consumers are cosmopolitan, open-minded and cultured.
The small Italian company, which started with 12 employees, has grown to almost 100 and since 2008 has had two offices, one in Milan and the other in New York.
She distributes her notebooks in bookstores, from Fnac to small shops in the city center and has managed to impose her identity.
"We followed the trend and this new need to write, despite the rise of e-mails", explains Maria Sebregondi.
This cultural signature accompanies the development of Moleskine: recently, the brand launched an exhibition "Detour" where architects or artists exhibit their own carnet.
In August, she also launched a leopard cover at the Locarno Film Festival.
Taking advantage of its success and cultural aura, Moleskine has diversified its products: bags, notebooks, pens, computer cases... The brand is available on a whole range of media.
A success that made some people envious: in the autumn of 2006, Modo Modo was bought by the investment fund SG Capital Europe, now Syntegra Capital, writing a new page in the history of Moleskine.
Why does the unemployment rate for disabled workers remain so high?
About 19% of disabled people are looking for work.
The 15th week for the employment of the disabled opens today.
Despite a proactive public policy introduced in 2005, the unemployment rate of disabled people is still twice as high as the average: 19%, compared to 9% for the general population.
Discouraging ?
"No", says Éric Blanchet, director general of Adapt, the association that organizes the week for the employment of the disabled".
"The progress made in the last 15 years is considerable".
"Back then, the unemployment rate was not doubled, but tripled".
"But there is still a lot of work to be done".
It must be said that for the unemployed disabled, there are still many obstacles to employment.
They are rather old: 37% are over 50 (on average 17%).
They have a low level of qualification: 80% do not have a baccalaureate and of the 2.3 million students in higher education, only 10 000 are disabled.
Finally, longterm unemployment is very high: 53% for the disabled, compared with 38% on average.
In short, these are all criteria which make it particularly difficult to return to employment and which "are at the heart of the problem", according to Christian Grapin, the managing director of Tremplin, an association set up in 1992 to help companies recruit disabled workers.
That's for the objective brakes.
The unspoken word remains, the mentality is changing, but too slowly.
A study carried out in April by the IMS-Entreprendre pour la Cité association indicated that the managers interviewed had "a low level of knowledge of disability", with an "overrepresentation of people in wheelchairs, mentally or intellectually disabled".
As a result, private enterprises with more than 20 employees are still far from the employment target of 6% of disabled workers, set by a law of 1987.
The last known figures, from 2008, show a ratio of 2.6%.
"We are now at around 3%", says Pierre Blanc, director general of Agefiph, the organisation responsible for collecting the contributions of companies that do not comply with this law.
The evidence: the number of establishments "taxed", as well as the amounts paid, decreased between 2007 and 2011, from 59 000 to 46 000 structures (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
"The 2005 law, which increased contributions, created a strong pressure on companies", explains Pierre Blanc.
"But this improvement also reflects a real awareness, especially in large groups".
According to the Ministry of Employment, only 59% of establishments with 20 to 49 employees employ disabled workers, compared with 82% of enterprises with 100 to 199 employees.
Hazard: "What happiness"
Before facing the Blues on Tuesday night (20:45) Eden Hazard and Georges Leekens have not hidden the pleasure they have from this friendly match.
We don't go so far as to say that there was collusion between them, but the image is symbolic.
Sitting side by side on the podium of the Stade de France, Leekens and Hazard have made peace.
Five months after his striker's temperamental gesture against Turkey, the Belgian coach has nothing but praise for him.
"I am very pleased with Eden, his progress and the fact that he is Belgian".
"I want to go on", the Lillois said.
As for the contrast between his performances in club and in selection, "it's a whole, he justified himself".
"In Lille, I'm there all year, which is not the case with Belgium".
"I need to get my act together".
Prepared for the match against Romania on Friday night, Hazard is coming to St. Denis to finally "shine".
But it also has the word "pleasure".
He has been a regular for the Blues since the age of seven and was a key part of their winning campaigns in 1998 and 2000.
"I've always been a supporter", he says.
This is bound to add to the 'special' character of this meeting.
Especially since in front, "there is Mathieu (Debuchy), Yohan (Cabaye) and Adil (Rami) ", he recalls.
"We just ran into each other".
"To be able to play against them, that's just happiness!"
Leekens, for his part, spoke with a certain glee of "pride".
"Pride" to play "a gala game".
"Proud" also to note - as a "neighbour" - that France has "become a very high-level team again" just over a year after the Knysna trauma.
"Laurent Blanc has done a great job", he said enthusiastically.
With Belgium missing out on the next Euro, the technician could be sharing a plane with the Blues heading... Brazil in 2014.
"Our little Belgians are getting big", he said.
"We're building something, the players are ambitious, they're hungry".
"You'll find out in the next few games". Including the one against France.
Portugal is very confident
Portugal under Paulo Bento will start with a lot of optimism in their return match against Bosnia (22h00), this Tuesday in Lisbon.
Both teams had a lack of realism.
"At the end of these 90 minutes, we will be a happy team and, most importantly, a happy country".
Paulo Bento is already seeing it in Poland and Ukraine.
For him, there is no shadow of a doubt, the Selecçao, which he has been in charge since September 2010, will qualify for Euro 2012.
Portugal is only 90 minutes away from happiness.
But there's a game to play, and an opponent, Bosnia, to unlock.
In view of the match 0-0 in the Zenica hell on Friday, it is obvious that the games are not made.
Portugal dominated the game for over an hour, but they were unable to score that precious goal, which would have relieved them.
"It's a good result, but it's a bit of a risk because we didn't score on the outside".
But at home, in their brightly lit Stadium of the Light in Lisbon, the Portuguese are convinced that they will be able to pass, in front of an audience that should be as boiling, even if the game is obviously "very close", said an optimistic but lucid Bento.
